(30, NULL, 'Clock ticking on amnesty for fake birth records, says NACC', 46, 'MANILA, Philippines — The National Authority for Child Care (NACC) has urged individuals who faked the birth records of children under their care to avail themselves of the rectification process allowed under the law, warning that the amnesty provision will only be available until March 28, 2029.\r\n\r\nSpeaking at a media forum, Assistant Secretary Rowena Macalintal cited Republic Act No. 11222, saying those who fail to file a petition within the 10-year period from the law’s effectivity in 2019 may no longer be covered by the amnesty and could face criminal, civil and administrative liabilities under existing laws.\r\n\r\n“Kung kayo po ay mayroong under custody na bata, iniwan sa inyo o inialok sa inyo, tapos iniregister mo ang sarili mo bilang nanay ng batang ito, ito po ay may criminal offense,” Macalintal said Thursday at the Department of Social Welfare and Development (DSWD) Central Office New Press Center.\r\n\r\n(If you have a child under your custody — one who was left with you or offered to you — and you register yourself as the child’s mother, that is a criminal offense.)\r\n\r\nShe said it constitutes illegal adoption and simulation of a birth certificate under the Revised Penal Code and Republic Act No. 1164.\r\n\r\nMacalintal said simulating or faking birth records carries serious penalties.\r\n\r\n“May kulong po ito na 8 to 10 years imprisonment. Mayroon din pong civil liability at administrative liability kung kayo po ay government employee,” she said.\r\n\r\n(This carries a penalty of eight to 10 years of imprisonment. There is also civil liability and administrative liability if you are a government employee.)\r\n\r\nThe NACC is a quasi-judicial agency attached to the DSWD. \r\n\r\nIf the simulation happened before 2019 and the child has been raised as the petitioner’s own, she said the petitioner may avail of the benefits under the Simulated Birth Rectification Act.\r\n\r\nUnder Republic Act No. 11222, simulation of birth record is defined as tampering with the civil registry to make it appear that a child was born to a person who is not the child’s biological mother, resulting in the loss of the child’s true identity and status.\r\n\r\nRectification of fake records\r\nThe law, signed on Feb. 21, 2019, and effective March 29, 2019, allows the rectification of simulated birth records through an administrative adoption process rather than court proceedings.\r\n\r\nBefore its enactment, families who faked birth records had to undergo judicial adoption under Republic Act No. 8552, or the Domestic Adoption Act of 1998. \r\n\r\nThe process was often costly and time-consuming and exposed petitioners to possible prosecution for falsification of public documents and simulation of births under the Revised Penal Code.\r\n\r\nRepublic Act No. 11222 provides amnesty to those who simulated birth records before its effectivity, provided the act was done in the best interest of the child and that a petition for adoption with application for rectification is filed within 10 years from effectivity.\r\n\r\nUnder Section 4 of the law, those who qualify “shall not be criminally, civilly, or administratively liable” for the act of simulation once the rectification process is successfully completed.\r\n\r\nThe law does not apply to cases involving child trafficking, abuse, exploitation or other illicit purposes, which remain prosecutable under existing laws.\r\n\r\nWho may qualify\r\nUnder the law, the child must have been living with and treated as the petitioners’ own son or daughter and must have been in their custody for at least three years before the law’s effectivity in 2019.\r\n\r\nThe implementing rules and regulations state that the petition must be filed with the Social Welfare and Development Office of the city or municipality where the child resides, regardless of where the simulated birth was registered.\r\n\r\nDSWD guidelines issued through Memorandum Circular No. 16, series of 2020, state that the child’s best interests remain the paramount consideration in all proceedings. \r\n\r\nSocial workers are required to conduct a comprehensive social case study report, including home visits, interviews and background checks, to determine whether the adoption and rectification will redound to the welfare of the child.\r\n\r\nIf the child is 10 years old or older, written consent is required. Consent of legitimate and adopted children of the adopter who are 10 years old or older may also be required under the law and its implementing rules.\r\n\r\nHow the rectification works\r\nMacalintal said the rectification process begins with filing a petition with the local Social Welfare and Development Office, which evaluates the application and endorses it to the DSWD field office.\r\n\r\nThe field office prepares a social case study report and submits a recommendation to the regional director, who forwards it to the DSWD secretary for final decision. The secretary must decide on the petition within 30 days from receipt of the recommendation.\r\n\r\nIf approved, an order of adoption is issued canceling the simulated birth record, directing the registration of the rectified birth record or foundling certificate, and ordering the issuance of a new birth certificate.\r\n\r\nThe administrative adoption order has the same legal effect as a decree of adoption issued under the Domestic Adoption Act of 1998.\r\n\r\n“I-file lang po ninyo ang inyong mga petition sa mga local government units, sa ating mga LSWDO para mapetition for the rectification ng simulated birth certificate. Kapag naissue na po yung adoption decree, pwede niyo na pong mapa-amend ang birth certificate na kayo po talaga ang lehitimong magulang ng bata na inampon ninyo at wala po kayong penalty,” she said.\r\n\r\n(Just file your petitions with your local government units, with our Local Social Welfare and Development Offices, so you can apply for the rectification of the simulated birth certificate. Once the adoption decree is issued, you can have the birth certificate amended to reflect that you are the child’s legitimate parent, and you will not incur any penalty.)\r\n\r\nShe added that the amnesty also covers those who cooperated in the simulation.\r\n\r\n“Pati na rin po yung mga kakuntsabang nurse, midwife, doctor na kasama pong naki-connive doon sa birth certificate, pati sila ay makaka-avail ng amnesty na pino-provide ng batas natin only until 2029,” Macalintal said.\r\n\r\n(This also includes the nurses, midwives or doctors who connived in the execution of the birth certificate — they, too, may avail themselves of the amnesty provided by the law, but only until 2029.)\r\n\r\nThe implementing rules also provide for the confidentiality of all records and proceedings. Unauthorized disclosure may be penalized under relevant laws, including the Data Privacy Act.\r\n\r\nIf a petition is denied, the petitioner may file a motion for reconsideration within 15 days, as provided in the rules. Appeals follow existing administrative procedures.\r\n\r\nDeadline: March 28, 2029\r\nThe law provides a 10-year window from March 29, 2019, to March 28, 2029, for qualified individuals to avail themselves of rectification and amnesty.\r\n\r\nAfter that date, applications will no longer be entertained under Republic Act No. 11222, and petitioners may have to pursue regular judicial adoption proceedings without the benefit of statutory amnesty.\r\n\r\nMacalintal urged families to coordinate with authorities while the amnesty remains in effect.\r\n\r\n“Kung mayroon po kayong kamag-anak o kakilala na nag-simulate ng birth certificate from 2019 backwards, makipag-coordinate po kayo sa NACC through our Regional Child Care Offices o kaya sa inyong Local Social Welfare Development Officers sa inyong mga LGUs para po ma-process na po natin ang rectification at adoption,” she said.\r\n\r\n(If you have a relative or know someone who simulated a birth certificate prior to 2019, coordinate with the NACC through our Regional Child Care Offices or with your Local Social Welfare and Development Officers in your local government units so the rectification and adoption can be processed.)\r\n\r\nAppeal to mothers in crisis\r\nMacalintal also appealed to mothers who may be struggling to care for their children not to abandon them in unsafe places.\r\n\r\n“Kung hindi niyo na po kayang alagaan pa ang inyong anak, hindi po kailangang itapon o iwan sa kung saan-saan kasi ilalagay lang po natin sila sa peligro at kapahamakan,” she said.\r\n\r\n(If you can no longer care for your child, there is no need to abandon them in unsafe places, as that would put them in danger. \r\n\r\n“Meron po tayong 148 prospective adoptive parents na nasa roster po ng NACC, waiting, praying na makapag-ampon at maka-match sila sa babies. Isuko po natin sa mga residential care facilities ng DSWD o kaya sa mga child caring agencies, o di kaya po sa ating mga social workers, sa ating mga safe havens, sa ospital, sa simbahan,” Macalintal said.\r\n\r\n(We have 148 prospective adoptive parents in the NACC roster who are waiting to adopt and be matched with babies. They may be surrendered to DSWD residential care facilities, child-caring agencies, social workers, safe havens, hospitals or churches.)\r\n\r\nShe said mothers who properly surrender their children will not face abandonment charges and will instead receive assistance.\r\n\r\n“Puwede po nating dalhin ang ating mga bata doon at hindi po kayo huhulihin. Hindi po kayo kakasuhan ng abandonment. Kayo po ay tutulungan. Ang unang protocol po ay mabigyan po ng counseling at intervention ang nanay para sana hindi niya kailangang i-let go yung kanyang anak,” Macalintal said.\r\n\r\n(You may bring your children there and you will not be arrested. You will not be charged with abandonment. You will be helped. The first protocol is to provide the mother with counseling and intervention so that she may not have to give up her child.)', 1, 3, '2026-02-13 06:44:02', '2026-02-15 10:18:24', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_698ec8323d6ae7.39015214.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(31, NULL, 'SWS: Cheating is common in PH, but so is forgiveness', 57, 'Cheating is a prevalent issue in the Philippines, as highlighted by a recent Social Weather Stations (SWS) survey. According to the survey conducted from November 24 to 30, 2025, 27% of adult Filipinos have either witnessed or experienced cheating in relationships. The forms of cheating reported include physical cheating (engaging in sexual or intimate activities with someone else), emotional cheating (developing romantic feelings for another person or confiding in someone else about personal issues instead of one\'s partner), and cyber cheating (maintaining secret social media accounts or engaging in clandestine online conversations).\r\n\r\nDespite the prevalence of cheating, the survey also revealed a positive trend towards forgiveness and the restoration of trust. Approximately 43% of respondents expressed belief in the possibility of rebuilding trust after an incident of cheating. This statistic indicates a strong inclination towards reconciliation and working through relationship challenges in the Filipino community.\r\n\r\nThe data underscores the need for open communication, trust-building exercises, and possibly professional counseling to address issues of infidelity in relationships. By acknowledging the various forms of cheating and understanding the emotional impact it can have on individuals and relationships, steps can be taken to promote healthier connections and foster a culture of forgiveness and resilience.\r\n\r\nMoving forward, it is essential for individuals and couples to engage in honest conversations about boundaries, expectations, and values within their relationships. By promoting transparency, mutual respect, and a commitment to addressing challenges constructively, the incidence of cheating can be minimized, and trust can be nurtured and strengthened over time.\r\n\r\nIn conclusion, the SWS survey sheds light on the complex dynamics of trust, forgiveness, and infidelity in Filipino relationships. By acknowledging the realities of cheating and embracing the possibility of rebuilding trust, individuals and couples can navigate relationship challenges with resilience and empathy, ultimately fostering stronger and more enduring connections.', 1, 3, '2026-02-13 06:46:47', '2026-02-15 10:18:20', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_698ec8d7a47345.36703281.png', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(32, NULL, 'Senate panel eyes passing anti-political dynasty bill before March ends', 98, 'Senator Risa Hontiveros said Friday that the Senate Committee on Electoral Reforms is planning to pass the bill seeking to prohibit political dynasties before March ends.  “It will be passed. Intensyon namin maipasa ito this session so bago matapos ang buwan ng Marso,” Hontiveros said during a joint committee meeting. (It will be passed. It is our intention to pass it this session, so before March ends.) Hontiveros, who chairs the electoral reforms panel, said she wants the anti-political dynasty law to cover up to the 4th degree of consanguinity. “Para sa akin ‘yun ang dapat, ‘yun ang ideal. Bilang isa sa mga authors sa Senate, ‘yun ang ipu-push ko. At the same time… I\'m working with six bills na iba-iba ang prescription. Fourth degree, third degree, second degree,” she said. (For me, that is what should be done, that is the ideal. As one of the authors in the Senate, that is what I will push. At the same time… I’m working on six bills with different prescriptions: fourth degree, third degree, second degree.) She said they will undergo a consensus building to reach a compromise. “Ang sa akin lang, whatever will be our final form, ‘yung tingin kong dapat or ideal na 4th degree or maaring sa mas marami sa colleagues ko, mas practical or mas reasonable at this point in time, 3rd degree or 2nd degree, basta ang importante sa akin, magkaroon kami ng batas na impactful, may kwenta,” she said. (For me, whatever will be our final form, what I think should be the ideal—4th degree—or for many of my colleagues, maybe more practical or more reasonable at this point in time, 3rd degree or 2nd degree, what’s important to me is that we have a law that is impactful and meaningful.) Hontiveros also said that the damage brought by a dynasty is known to the public. “Kung saan nangingibabaw ang konsentrasyon ng kapangyarihan sa ilang pamilya, madalas matatagpuan rin ang korapsyon, kahirapan, at kakulangan ng pananagutan o accountability,” she said. (Where the concentration of power in a few families prevails, corruption, poverty, and a lack of accountability are often also found.) “Sa halip ng serbisyong publiko sa ordinaryong Pilipino, personal na interes at pakinabang ang madalas na nagiging sentro. Nandito tayo ngayon para baguhin ito,” she added. (Instead of public service for ordinary Filipinos, personal interest and gain often become the focus. We are here now to change this.) Meanwhile, Bacolod City Mayor Greg Gasataya said he is in favor of starting the discussion and coming up with a clear framework on the prohibition of dynasties. There are currently six bills on political dynasties filed in the Senate. — RSJ, GMA Integrated News\r\n\r\n---\r\nAuthor: GMA News\r\nSource: GMA News\r\nPublished: February 13, 2026', 1, 5, '2026-02-13 07:12:54', '2026-02-15 10:18:13', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_698ed0880aa398.19924945.jpg', NULL, 'external_import', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(33, NULL, 'ByteDance’s new AI video model goes viral as China looks for second DeepSeek moment', 98, 'Already have Rappler+? Sign in to listen to groundbreaking journalism. This is AI generated summarization, which may have errors. For context, always refer to the full article. BYTEDANCE. The Bytedance logo is seen in this illustration taken February 8, 2025. BEIJING, China – ByteDance’s new video-generating artificial intelligence model has already impressed the likes of Elon Musk and gone viral in China, where it has been compared to DeepSeek and won praise for its ability to produce cinematic storylines with just a few prompts. While text-centric AI models such as OpenAI’s ChatGPT and DeepSeek’s R1 have become widely adopted, models specialized in generating videos and pictures represent the next frontier in the technology’s potential for disruption. ByteDance, which officially unveiled Seedance 2.0 on Thursday, February 12, said in a statement that the system was designed for professional film, e-commerce, and advertising productions, because it was capable of processing text, images, audio, and video simultaneously, lowering the cost of creating content. The product launch comes as China and investors around the world are on the lookout for a successor to Chinese startup DeepSeek’s R1 and V3 models whose global debut early in 2025 triggered a systemic shock. On Chinese social media, Seedance 2.0 drew comparisons to DeepSeek’s meteoric rise to fame. “Early last year, the release of DeepSeek-R1 sparked heated debate in the US tech community over a ‘Sputnik moment’,” Chinese state-backed newspaper Global Times wrote in an editorial on Wednesday. “This year, the continued breakout success of Seedance 2.0 and similar innovations has gone even further, giving rise to a wave of admiration for China within Silicon Valley.” The buzz generated by Seedance 2.0 was underscored when the world’s richest man Elon Musk replied to a post praising the model on his social media platform X by commenting, “It’s happening fast.” Users on China’s Weibo microblogging platform shared videos generated by the AI model that showcased the complexity and image quality of its output, no matter how bizarre the prompt. One two-minute video, which had been viewed around a million times on Weibo, depicted rapper and record producer Ye, formerly known as Kanye West, and reality TV star Kim Kardashian, as characters in a palace drama set in Imperial China, speaking and singing in Mandarin. Hashtags related to Seedance 2.0 have racked up tens of millions of clicks on Weibo, including one from state-owned newspaper Beijing Daily that read “from DeepSeek to Seedance, China’s AI has succeeded.” – Rappler.com\r\n\r\n---\r\nAuthor: Rappler\r\nSource: Rappler\r\nPublished: February 13, 2026', 1, 5, '2026-02-13 07:13:53', '2026-02-15 10:18:09', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_698ecfe8967e23.71136099.jpg', NULL, 'external_import', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(34, NULL, 'PNP: LRT-1 has no contributory negligence in fall incident', 98, 'The Philippine National Police (PNP) sees no liability on the part of the management of the Light Rail Transit Line 1 (LRT-1) in the fatal fall of a student from FPJ Station in Quezon City. “Magkakaroon lang po ng pananagutan ang LRT na kung may nakita silang contributory negligence sa parte po ng LRT,” PNP spokesperson Police Brigadier General Randulf Tuaño said at a press briefing. (The LRT will only be held accountable if the police find contributory negligence on the part of the LRT.) “Pero sa ngayon po, wala po silang nakikita na contributory negligence sa part po ng LRT,” he added. (But for now, they do not find any contributory negligence on the part of the LRT.) The Quezon City Police District (QCPD) conducted an investigation into the incident involving a male student who reportedly fell from FPJ Station around 10:30 a.m. on Wednesday. According to the QCPD, a CCTV footage provided by the LRT-1 management showed the victim walking back and forth around the area. He was also looking at the road. After a few minutes, the incident happened. A vehicle on the road also hit him after the fall. The driver was placed under police custody in accordance with the PNP’s standard operating procedures (SOP) as the incident involved a fatality. The driver was released after the father of the victim executed a notarized letter stating that he is not pursuing a complaint against the driver. —AOL, GMA Integrated News\r\n\r\n---\r\nAuthor: GMA News\r\nSource: GMA News\r\nPublished: February 13, 2026', 1, 5, '2026-02-13 07:14:08', '2026-02-15 10:18:06', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_698ecf9331f806.00018761.webp', NULL, 'external_import', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(36, NULL, 'Robin Padilla: ‘Kids are weak’ remark based on suicide data', 48, 'MANILA, Philippines—When he called today’s kids “weak,” it was not just an opinion but a reality supported by studies and records, according to Sen. Robin Padilla.\r\n\r\nPadilla took to Facebook to explain his remark during Wednesday’s hearing of the Senate committee on public information and mass media on various measures regarding children’s safety on social media.\r\n\r\n“As the chairman of the Committee on Public Information and Mass Media, it is my mandate to be truthful to the people and not be plastic or pretentious in what I say, because that is the truth,” he explained in Filipino.\r\n\r\n“It’s the suicide data we studied in our office that show today’s youth are weak; it is not merely the result of our suggestion or opinion,” he added.\r\n\r\nAnd this was supported by studies from other progressive countries and data from the World Health Organization, according to him\r\n\r\nPadilla also cited a 2021 survey, which showed that nearly one in five (about 20%) Filipino youth aged 15 to 24 have thought about ending their lives.\r\n\r\nSuicide attempts among young people, meanwhile,  increased to 7.5% in 2021, a 150 percent increase from the 3% recorded in 2013, while approximately 46% of all recorded suicide cases since 2010 involve young people aged 10–35, the senator added.\r\n\r\n“So if you want to help address this issue concerning the youth, do something about it and stop talking about me. Act on the data, not on my statement,” he said.\r\n\r\n“Focus on what is happening to our youth, not on me,” he added.', 1, 3, '2026-02-13 07:40:29', '2026-02-15 10:18:03', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_698ed66e3fc1d9.39182596.png', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(37, NULL, 'The Importance of Human-like Movement in Prosthetic Limbs', 54, 'As artificial intelligence-powered prosthetic arms become more common, understanding how people respond to them is crucial. Acceptance of these devices depends not only on their functionality but also on how natural they feel. Researchers used virtual reality to create the illusion that a participant\'s arm had been replaced with a robotic prosthetic, and then tested how different movement speeds influenced embodiment, including body ownership, sense of agency, usability, and social impressions.\r\n\r\nThe findings revealed a clear pattern: when the prosthetic arm moved too quickly or too slowly, participants felt less connected to it and rated it as less usable. However, when the arm moved at a moderate pace similar to natural human reaching, taking about one second to complete the motion, participants reported the strongest sense that the arm felt like part of their own body. This suggests that future AI-enabled prostheses should prioritize human-compatible timing rather than speed alone, as designers may need to tune movement patterns to align with what the brain expects from a natural limb.\r\n\r\nThe implications of this research extend beyond prosthetic arms. Other technologies that function as extensions of the body, including supernumerary robotic limbs, exoskeletons, and wearable robots, could also benefit from movement that mirrors natural human rhythm. Researchers also plan to explore how long-term use changes perception, as even a fast and highly capable robotic limb may start to feel more normal and easier to operate with continued daily use. Virtual reality allows scientists to test emerging prosthetic technologies and control systems in a safe and controlled setting, making it possible to evaluate psychological responses, user acceptance, and design considerations early in development.', 1, 5, '2026-02-13 07:41:05', '2026-02-15 10:18:00', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_698ed591a93ab5.09931171.webp', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(38, NULL, 'Kris Aquino Celebrates Milestone Birthday with Resilience and Hope', 55, 'As Kris Aquino approaches her 55th birthday on Valentine\'s Day, the beloved media personality is reflecting on her health journey with remarkable optimism. In a recent Instagram post, Aquino shared her simple yet profound birthday wish: to live long enough to reach 60 and qualify for both a senior citizen and person with disability (PWD) card. Despite battling autoimmune diseases and undergoing a six-week hospital stay, she expressed gratitude for her progress, noting that she can now walk unaided and is rarely using her wheelchair.\r\n\r\nLooking ahead, Aquino plans to co-produce an on-camera podcast and is hopeful about rebuilding her immunity, which is currently compromised. She also touched on her son Bimby\'s emerging career, emphasizing that she prefers being a supportive mother rather than a \"mamager\" and has entrusted his career planning to someone she trusts. By openly sharing her medical challenges and future aspirations, Aquino continues to demonstrate her trademark transparency and resilience, inspiring her followers with her positive outlook and determination to overcome obstacles.', 1, 5, '2026-02-13 07:49:00', '2026-02-15 10:17:56', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_698ed76c31b5b9.39041023.webp', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(39, 36, 'Robin Padilla inalmahan ng psychologist sa talak tungkol sa depression', 48, 'HINDI napigilang mag-react ng psychologist na si Riyan Portuguez sa naging pahayag ni Sen. Robin Padilla patungkol sa depresyon.\r\n\r\nSa kanyang “Your Millenial Psychologist” Facebook page, ibinahagi niya ang mga dahilan kung bakit hindi uso ang salitang depresyon noong panahon ng senador.\r\n\r\n“Noong panahon po kasi ninyo [Robin Padilla] maraming mga tao partikular na ang kabataan ang natatakot na magsabi dahil sa katulad po ninyo na kaysa maunawaan eh hinuhusgahan kaagad na ‘weak’ o mahina kapag may pinagdadaanan,” sabi ng psychologist\r\n\r\nPagpapatuloy pa niya, “Maraming katulad po ninyo noon ang nagtatago sa dilim para sarilinin lang ang problema at magkunwaring ‘okay lang.’ Paano mo makikita eh nagtatago nga?\r\n\r\nKaya naman pakiusap ni Riyan na sana ay huwag danasin ng sinumang miyembro ng pamilya ni Robin ang depression para lang maintindihan niyo ang ibig sabihin ng pagkakaroon ng ganitong karamdamang mental.\r\n\r\nAng depresyon ay isang clinical diagnosis na kinakailangang gamutin sa pamamagitan ng therapy at mga gamot. Makakatulong rin para malabanan ito sa pamamagitan ng pag-e-exercise, meditation, pagkakaroon ng iba pang libangan, pagdarasal, at mga suporta mula sa pamilya at malalapit na kaibigan.\r\n\r\nMatatandaang noong Miyerkules, February 11, sinabi ni Robin sa Senate Committe on Public Information and Mass Media na hindi uso ang depression.\r\n\r\n“Ang mga bata po ngayon, sad to say, you are weak.\r\n\r\nHindi kayo katulad noong panahon namin na hindi kami iyakin. Natuto kami sa kalsada. Natuto kami na huwag umupo at umiyak,” sey ni Robin.', 1, 3, '2026-02-13 07:52:55', '2026-02-15 10:18:59', 3, 1, 'developing', 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_698ed857340fd5.35733551.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(40, 36, 'Generational Divide: Kuya Kim Responds to Senator Padilla\'s Critique of Modern Youth', 98, 'In a recent Facebook post, GMA Network\'s Kuya Kim Atienza offered a thoughtful response to Senator Robin Padilla\'s controversial statement about today\'s youth being \"weak\" during a Senate committee hearing. Padilla had reminisced about the 1980s and 1990s, claiming that children from his generation were happier because they played outside, implying that current youth are somehow less resilient. The senator suggested that topics like depression were not discussed in his time, seemingly dismissing the mental health challenges faced by younger generations.\r\n\r\nAtienza approached the topic with compassion, emphasizing the importance of understanding and supporting individuals struggling with mental health challenges. He highlighted the existence of 24/7 crisis hotlines as evidence of the ongoing need for mental health support, regardless of generational perspectives. His response advocated for kindness and empathy, noting that while generational experiences may differ, the fundamental need for support remains constant. By addressing Padilla\'s comments with nuance and sensitivity, Atienza demonstrated a more inclusive approach to understanding the complex experiences of younger generations in an increasingly digital and challenging world.', 1, 5, '2026-02-13 08:01:00', '2026-02-15 10:19:02', 3, 1, 'developing', 2, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_698eda3cdfed32.89317484.jpeg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(41, NULL, 'Cardinal Tagle Assumes Titular Diocese of Albano in Historic Ceremony', 97, 'Cardinal Luis Antonio Tagle has formally taken possession of the Titular Diocese of Albano in a significant ceremony held at the Albano Cathedral in Italy. The event was well-attended by Filipinos, Tagle\'s family, and members of the Pontificio Collegio Filipino (PCF). As one of the seven historic sees surrounding Rome, the suburbicarian Diocese of Albano is traditionally assigned to high-ranking cardinals. Pope Leo XIV\'s decree, issued on May 24, appointed Tagle to this ecclesiastical office, praising his \"extraordinary intellectual gifts, sensibility, competence, wisdom, fidelity, and zealous industriousness\" in his role as Pro-Prefect of the Dicastery for Evangelization.\r\n\r\nThe ceremony held special significance, coinciding with the 64th anniversary of the Pontificio Collegio Filipino\'s inauguration. Originally established by Giuseppe Cardinal Pizzardo, the college-seminary was dedicated to Our Lady of Peace and Good Voyage, with the purpose of supporting young Filipino priests undergoing formation in Rome. Notably, the title was previously briefly assigned to Cardinal Robert Francis Prevost, who was elected pope on May 8 before he could take possession. Tagle, who was elevated to the rank of Cardinal-Bishop by the late Pope Francis in 2020, continues the traditional practice where cardinal bishops hold a titular diocese while the administrative leadership remains with the local ecclesiastical authorities.', 1, 5, '2026-02-13 08:10:01', '2026-02-15 10:17:40', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_698edc594612b6.31317226.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(42, NULL, 'Palace Press Officer Critiques Vice President Duterte as \"Emotional Vulture\" Amid National Concerns', 48, 'MANILA, Philippines — Claire Castro, the Press Officer for the Palace, has sharply criticized Vice President Sara Duterte, labeling her an \"emotional vulture\" for allegedly feigning concern for the nation while lacking concrete solutions to its pressing issues. Castro\'s remarks came in response to Duterte\'s recent comments expressing uncertainty about the future of the Philippines, questioning whether the country would still exist by the time of the 2028 national elections. Castro suggested that the vice president is overlooking the ongoing efforts of the Marcos administration to tackle these challenges, stating, \"It is saddening because this is a Duterte move, showing the characteristic of an emotional vulture — pretending to be concerned for the state of the nation when in fact she admitted that she doesn’t want to help the President in his projects.\"\r\n\r\nIn her statements, Castro issued a stark warning about the potential consequences of electing a \"Manchurian candidate\" in the next election cycle, implying that such a leader could compromise the nation\'s resources. While she refrained from directly naming Duterte, Castro referenced the vice president\'s previous interactions with Chinese officials and her reluctance to address issues surrounding the West Philippine Sea. Additionally, Castro accused Duterte of spreading misinformation about both her and the Marcos administration and recalled a disturbing comment made by Duterte regarding a hitman who could target key political figures, including President Bongbong Marcos. Concluding her remarks, Castro urged Duterte to \"spread love, not fake news, not immorality,\" signaling the escalating tensions within the current administration as the country approaches a critical electoral period.', 1, 5, '2026-02-13 08:24:02', '2026-02-15 10:16:50', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_698edfa2d9d198.65769201.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(43, NULL, 'Resurgence of Japanese Swordsmithing Attracts New Generation Amidst Declining Craft', 57, 'MISATO, Saitama, Japan — In the soot-covered studio of swordsmith Akihira Kawasaki, the rhythmic clang of an apprentice hammering red-hot steel resonates, highlighting a traditional craft experiencing a revival. The katana, a hallmark of Japanese craftsmanship, is captivating a new audience, particularly younger women, despite the dwindling number of blademakers in the country. This renewed interest is largely fueled by pop culture phenomena, including the popular video game “Touken Ranbu,” which anthropomorphizes swords as attractive characters, alongside other media such as the U.S. series “Shogun” and the anime “Demon Slayer.”\r\n\r\nKawasaki, 57, expressed his optimism about the growing enthusiasm among young people for swords. He noted a significant shift from the past, when sword enthusiasts were predominantly male and often dismissive of newcomers. \"It was no fun community,\" he remarked, highlighting a cultural barrier that new fans like 25-year-old Minori Takumi are breaking down. After discovering “Touken Ranbu” as a teenager, Takumi’s fascination with the game led her to explore real swords at museums, eventually becoming a curator at the Bizen Osafune Sword Museum. She credits the game for deepening her appreciation of the craft and sparking her passion for the katana\'s intricate details.\r\n\r\nDespite this cultural renaissance, the swordsmithing profession faces significant challenges, with the number of blademakers in Japan halving over the past 40 years to approximately 160, many of whom are elderly. Tetsuya Tsubouchi, head of the All Japan Swordsmith Association\'s business unit, noted that the demanding apprenticeship, lasting at least five years without pay, deters potential young recruits. Furthermore, prevailing attitudes within the industry favor ancient swords over newly crafted ones, making it difficult for contemporary swordsmiths like Kawasaki to thrive financially. While his pieces command high prices due to their artistry and craftsmanship, the broader market remains difficult, necessitating a shift in perception for modern katana to be recognized as contemporary art rather than mere antiques.', 1, 5, '2026-02-13 08:29:41', '2026-02-15 10:09:37', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_698ee0f5bab050.21494974.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(44, NULL, 'Senate Bill Seeks to Broaden Voting Accessibility for Vulnerable Sectors', 46, 'A new legislative initiative in the Senate aims to significantly enhance the accessibility of polling places for vulnerable sectors, including persons with disabilities (PWDs), pregnant women, senior citizens, and indigenous peoples (IPs). Senate Bill No. 1698, filed by Senator Mark Villar and titled “An Act Enhancing Accessibility in the Voting of Senior Citizens, Persons with Disabilities, Pregnant Women, and Indigenous Peoples, Amending for the Purpose Republic Act No. 10366,” seeks to build upon existing legislation. Republic Act No. 10366, enacted in 2013, empowered the Commission on Elections (COMELEC) to establish accessible precincts specifically for PWDs and senior citizens. However, Senator Villar highlighted that despite this progress, substantial gaps persist, particularly for pregnant women and indigenous communities. Many individuals from these groups continue to encounter considerable obstacles, such as physical barriers at voting sites, difficulties with transportation, and geographic challenges in remote areas, which collectively undermine their fundamental right to participate fully in democratic processes. Villar emphasized that true democracy necessitates the hearing of every voice, asserting that current hurdles faced by these citizens are \"unnecessary.\"\r\n\r\nIf enacted, Senate Bill No. 1698 would mandate a more robust set of requirements for accessible polling places. The proposed measure stipulates that voting venues must be situated in locations easily reachable by public transportation and must be entirely free from physical impediments. Furthermore, it requires the provision of essential infrastructure and services tailored for vulnerable voters, including transport wheelchairs, ramps, railings, well-maintained sidewalks, adequate lighting, and proper ventilation. The bill\'s core objective is to empower the COMELEC to proactively designate and prepare polling places that prioritize inclusivity, thereby alleviating the physical and logistical burdens currently faced by these sectors on election day. By ensuring that no Filipino is disenfranchised due to accessibility issues, the legislation aims to uphold the principle of equal opportunity in electoral participation. The proposed measure has since been referred to the Senate Committee on Electoral Reforms and People Participation for detailed review and public hearings.', 1, 5, '2026-02-13 08:42:20', '2026-02-15 10:09:19', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_698ee3ec46c1a1.60184322.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(45, NULL, '\"Alien-Like\" Sea Slugs Discovered in UK Rock Pools: A Glimpse into Changing Marine Ecosystems', 95, 'Marine researchers in southwest England have made an exciting discovery of non-native sea hares, specifically the Aplysia depilans species, during a Rock Pool Project event at Mount Batten Beach. These unusual sea slugs, which can grow up to 40cm long and weigh 380g, were initially mistaken for seaweed by a young participant and his father. Zak Russell, the project\'s leader, described the creatures as \"alien-like\" and noted that two specimens were found during the same session, potentially indicating a broader environmental shift.\r\n\r\nExperts from the Marine Biological Association suggest that warming waters and increased storm activity might be facilitating the arrival of these rare sea slugs on British shores. While the sighting is preliminary, marine conservation researchers like Loretta Kwok view such discoveries as opportunities to inspire wonder and enhance understanding of coastal ecosystems. Russell advised careful observation, recommending that anyone encountering sea slugs should use gloves and a large bucket to minimize potential harm while appreciating these fascinating marine organisms.', 1, 5, '2026-02-13 08:52:05', '2026-02-15 10:09:13', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_698ee6358da5f3.90375822.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(46, NULL, 'Damian Lillard Stuns in Return, Wins Third NBA 3-Point Crown Amid Achilles Recovery', 56, 'In a performance few saw coming, Damian Lillard captured his third NBA 3-Point Contest title Saturday night despite not playing in a game since April 27 while recovering from a torn Achilles. The Portland Trail Blazers star joined Larry Bird and Craig Hodges as the only three-time champions in event history, adding to his back-to-back victories in 2023 and 2024. Lillard narrowly advanced from the first round after catching Donovan Mitchell with a dramatic late surge, drilling nine of his final 10 shots to post 27 points and electrify the crowd at Intuit Dome. In the championship round, Lillard left no doubt, pouring in 30 points to outlast Kon Knueppel and Devin Booker. Booker, the 2018 champion, appeared poised to steal the win but missed his final three moneyballs, sealing Lillard’s victory. The moment was especially meaningful for Lillard, who rejoined Portland last offseason after a brief stint with the Milwaukee Bucks and signed a three-year deal amid uncertainty about his recovery timeline. While his return to regular-season action remains pending, his shooting display offered a strong reminder that one of the league’s premier marksmen is inching closer to full strength.\r\n\r\n---\r\nAuthor: Shelwin Buenaventura\r\nSource: MBC Chat\r\nPublished: February 16, 2026', 1, 8, '2026-02-16 01:34:07', '2026-02-16 03:14:10', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/chat_media/2026/02/thumb_6992740fcf108.jpg', NULL, 'mbc_chat', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(47, NULL, 'Flood Control Funds at Center of Revilla\'s Latest Legal Battle', 48, 'Former Senator Bong Revilla Jr. faces another legal challenge as the Sandiganbayan entered a \"not guilty\" plea on his behalf for a malversation charge involving a P92.8-million flood control project in Bulacan. During a Monday hearing, Revilla declined to enter a personal plea, a standard procedure that allows the legal process to move forward while preserving his right to a fair trial.\r\n\r\nThe case involves multiple DPWH officials, including engineers and an accountant, and alleges misappropriation of funds intended for critical infrastructure. This is not Revilla\'s first encounter with legal scrutiny, as he was previously involved in the notorious PDAF \"pork barrel\" scam, from which he was ultimately acquitted. The current charge highlights ongoing concerns about potential corruption and misuse of public funds in government projects, with the Sandiganbayan set to thoroughly examine the evidence presented by both prosecution and defense.', 1, 5, '2026-02-16 02:32:07', '2026-02-16 03:14:06', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_699281d969ebe0.12491783.webp', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(48, NULL, 'Filipino Farmers Alarmed Over Falling Onion Prices as Imports Linger', 49, 'The Philippine Department of Agriculture (DA) has reported that imported onion supplies are inadequate to substantially lower domestic red onion prices, following complaints from farmers in Nueva Ecija about a significant drop in prices. Agriculture Secretary Francisco Tiu Laurel Jr. stated that while farmers have raised alarms regarding an influx of imported onions in cold storage facilities across Central Luzon, the data indicates that these imports are primarily filling a supply gap rather than flooding the market. He has directed the Bureau of Plant Industry (BPI) to investigate the situation to safeguard farmers\' interests while keeping onions affordable for consumers.\r\n\r\nCurrent statistics reveal that cold storage facilities contain 4,454.09 metric tons of red onions and 5,271.15 metric tons of yellow onions, predominantly from imports. The average price for red onions is approximately P30.36 per kilogram, with supplies expected to last until mid-March. The DA emphasized the need to consider the anticipated seasonal surge in local onion production, projected to peak between March and April, when evaluating the market dynamics. The BPI indicated that existing import clearances for around 8,000 metric tons of red onions are valid until mid-February, and even with all pending shipments, the imported stock may only sustain until early March. The DA is committed to balancing consumer needs and farmer livelihoods amid these fluctuating prices.', 1, 5, '2026-02-16 02:41:19', '2026-02-16 03:14:03', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_699283cfb2b488.98934192.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(49, NULL, 'Warming Oceans Spell Disaster for Vital Coral Reef Ecosystems', 59, 'Coral reefs, often referred to as the bustling cities of the underwater world, are crucial ecosystems that occupy less than one percent of the ocean floor yet support an incredible 25 percent of all marine species. Unfortunately, these essential habitats are under threat from a worsening crisis characterized by widespread coral bleaching, primarily driven by rising ocean temperatures. A recent study published in *Nature Communications* reveals a bleak outlook, noting that the \"Third Global Bleaching Event\" has resulted in the most extensive damage on record, while a \"Fourth Global Bleaching Event\" is currently manifesting with alarming intensity.\r\n\r\nSean Connolly, a senior scientist with the Panama-based Smithsonian Tropical Research Institute, emphasized the unprecedented scale of destruction from the Third Bleaching Event, marking it as the most severe and widespread incident documented to date. This alarming trend indicates a dire future for coral populations, which are now grappling with consecutive catastrophic events. The study, conducted by the U.S. National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration\'s (NOAA) Coral Reef Watch program, examined an extensive dataset of over 15,000 global reef surveys collected between June 2014 and May 2017. The findings were stark, revealing that approximately 80 percent of the surveyed reefs suffered moderate to severe loss of color and essential nutrients, with over 10 percent of individual corals directly impacted. Alarmingly, 35 percent of these corals were found to be either dying or already dead. By utilizing advanced satellite heat-stress data, researchers were able to project the global extent of this devastation, indicating that 51 percent of coral reefs worldwide are now at risk.', 1, 5, '2026-02-16 02:49:19', '2026-02-16 03:14:00', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_699285af717ca0.02098744.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(50, NULL, '28 Lives Lost: Army Exposes Violent Tactics of Communist Rebels in Negros Island', 47, 'The Philippine Army\'s 3rd Infantry Division (3ID) has reported a disturbing pattern of violence on Negros Island, revealing that at least 28 people have been killed since March 2025 by alleged communist terrorist group (CTG) remnants. In a recent statement, the division highlighted the brutal murder of 74-year-old Leonora Anguit, who was shot outside her home in Kabankalan City on February 3rd. The Armando Sumayang Jr. Command of the New People\'s Army claimed responsibility for her killing, alleging she was a military informant linked to a previous encounter where seven of their members were killed during a government operation.\r\n\r\nThe military emphasized that these victims are not combatants but ordinary citizens, including farmers and elderly residents, whose only \"crime\" was choosing peace over violence. According to 3ID, an average of two people have been killed monthly, with incidents designed to intimidate communities and disrupt local cooperation with authorities. The division has called on the Commission on Human Rights and other organizations to conduct independent investigations, stressing that these killings represent a systematic attack on civilian safety. While acknowledging the ongoing threat, military officials remain confident that local residents will continue supporting peace and security efforts in the region.', 1, 5, '2026-02-16 02:59:45', '2026-02-16 03:13:57', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_6992882169c9f7.88221542.png', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0);
