(109, NULL, 'Zuckerberg Confronts Allegations of Youth Mental Health Harm in Landmark Trial', 54, 'In a high-stakes trial addressing youth social media addiction, Meta CEO Mark Zuckerberg defended his platforms against allegations of deliberately targeting young users. The lawsuit centers on a California woman who claims Instagram and YouTube negatively impacted her mental health during childhood, arguing that these platforms intentionally designed features to hook young users despite knowing potential psychological risks.\r\n\r\nZuckerberg faced intense questioning from lawyer Mark Lanier, who presented internal Meta documents suggesting strategic plans to attract younger users. When confronted with a 2018 Instagram presentation stating \"If we want to win big with teens, we must bring them in as tweens,\" Zuckerberg argued that the statement was being mischaracterized. He maintained that while Meta discussed creating child-friendly platform versions, they ultimately did not implement such services. Furthermore, Zuckerberg suggested that age verification is complex and suggested device manufacturers should bear more responsibility for protecting young users.\r\n\r\nThe trial represents a broader legal challenge against social media companies, with thousands of cases alleging these platforms contribute to a youth mental health crisis. Previous investigations have revealed internal research showing Meta\'s awareness of potential psychological harm, including findings that some teens reported Instagram negatively impacting their body image. While Meta and Google deny these allegations and point to user safety features, the lawsuit could potentially challenge Big Tech\'s legal protections against user harm claims. Notably, competitors Snap and TikTok have already settled with the plaintiff, adding weight to the ongoing scrutiny of social media\'s impact on young users.', 1, 8, '2026-02-19 05:51:14', '2026-02-20 07:19:41', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_6996a4d28a7c41.29820976.webp', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(110, NULL, 'Testing Media', 101, 'Testing Media for RSN\n\n---\nAuthor: Cloyd\nSource: MBC Chat\nPublished: February 19, 2026\n', 1, 1, '2026-02-19 06:01:16', '2026-02-20 07:19:38', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/chat_media/2026/02/thumb_6996a72cee906.jpg', NULL, 'mbc_chat', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(112, NULL, 'PNP backs Marcos order to craft strategy vs ’dirty money’', 46, 'MANILA, Philippines — Philippine National Police (PNP) Chief Gen. Jose Melencio Nartatez Jr. said the agency supports President Ferdinand Marcos Jr.’s order for the government to craft a national strategy against money laundering.\r\n\r\n“The PNP is fully committed to President Marcos’ directive. We are ready to integrate our investigative powers with [the] AMLC (Anti-Money Laundering Council) in running after organized crime groups and syndicates,” Nartatez said in a statement on Friday.\r\n\r\n“High-risk sectors such as real estate, casinos, and import/export businesses will be closely monitored while international cooperation with foreign law enforcement agencies will be strengthened to track illicit funds entering or leaving the Philippines,” he added.\r\n\r\nThe directive came through Memorandum Circular No. 113 dated Feb. 12.\r\n\r\nThe memorandum ordered government agencies concerned to “actively participate” in drafting and to ensure their institutional plans were aligned with the National Anti-Money Laundering, Counter-Terrorism and Counter-Proliferation Financing Strategy for 2026–2030.\r\n\r\nIt also tasked the AMLC in particular to provide “technical and administrative support, issue timelines and monitor compliance” of the government agencies concerned.\r\n\r\nNartatez said the PNP will “enhance inter-agency cooperation, share data and participate in joint operations” to support the president’s directive.\r\n\r\nThe top cop noted that the police force, particularly its Anti-Cybercrime Group and Criminal Investigation and Detection Group, was undergoing training in financial forensics and detecting trends in financial crimes and money laundering.\r\n\r\n“The PNP is also upgrading its digital infrastructure, technologies, and data analytics tools for detecting suspicious financial transactions, including cross-border alerts,” he added.', 1, 13, '2026-02-20 06:56:43', '2026-02-20 07:19:35', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_699805ab3e7390.21456873.jpeg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0);
