(113, NULL, 'Series of diesel price hikes cued to enter third month', 49, 'MANILA, Philippines — Filipino motorists are bracing for yet another round of fuel price increases next week, marking a concerning trend that sees diesel prices on track for their ninth consecutive weekly hike. This sustained uptrend is poised to push the overall series of petroleum product price adjustments into its third month, placing further strain on household budgets and business operations across the archipelago.\r\n\r\nAccording to initial market indications shared by Leo Bellas, president of Jetti Petroleum, on Friday, the per-liter price of diesel is anticipated to climb by an estimated 40 centavos to 60 centavos. This projected increase, while seemingly modest per liter, accumulates significantly over weeks and months, especially for high-volume consumers like public transport operators and logistics companies.\r\n\r\nThe primary catalyst for this persistent upward pressure on fuel prices stems from escalating geopolitical tensions in the Middle East. Bellas specifically cited \"concerns over military activities in the region\" which have significantly \"increased the likelihood of US strikes on Iran.\" This heightened state of alert and potential for direct conflict has dampened any hope for a swift diplomatic resolution, creating an environment of uncertainty that directly impacts global oil markets. Investors and traders react to such developments by factoring in a \"risk premium,\" driving up crude oil prices on fears of supply disruptions, particularly from the critical Strait of Hormuz, a vital chokepoint for a substantial portion of the world\'s oil shipments.\r\n\r\nBeyond the immediate threat of conflict, Bellas also highlighted another crucial factor offsetting any potential price relief: \"rising freight and premium due to geopolitical risks.\" The instability in key shipping lanes, especially in regions like the Red Sea and Gulf of Aden, has led to increased insurance costs for vessels, longer rerouting journeys to avoid conflict zones, and a general scarcity of ships willing to traverse high-risk areas. These operational challenges translate directly into higher shipping costs for refined petroleum products, which are then passed on to importing countries like the Philippines. The \"premium\" refers to the additional cost added to the base price of oil or refined products due to perceived supply risks or increased demand for secure, timely delivery.\r\n\r\nInterestingly, Bellas noted that \"this week’s gasoline MOPS [Mean of Platts Singapore] prices have actually softened due to healthy regional inventories and supply.\" MOPS is the pricing benchmark for refined petroleum products in Asia, and a softening here would typically suggest a potential for a price rollback. However, the pervasive influence of rising freight costs and the geopolitical risk premium have effectively \"offset the prospect of a potential price rollback\" for gasoline, meaning consumers will likely see either minimal changes or even slight increases for gasoline as well, despite favorable underlying supply conditions.\r\n\r\nThe cumulative effect of these price hikes is expected to ripple through the Philippine economy. Consumers will face higher costs for transportation, and businesses will grapple with increased operational expenses, potentially leading to inflationary pressures on basic goods and services. Public utility vehicle (PUV) operators, particularly jeepney and bus drivers, are often among the first to feel the pinch, prompting calls for fare adjustments or government subsidies to maintain their livelihoods. The government, in turn, will be closely monitoring global oil developments and domestic inflation, with potential considerations for measures such as fuel subsidies or adjustments to excise taxes to mitigate the impact on the populace. The outlook remains challenging, with Filipino consumers heavily reliant on global geopolitical stability for any respite from the ongoing fuel price surge.', 1, 13, '2026-02-20 07:00:15', '2026-02-20 07:19:32', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_6998067f79ef18.23679274.jpeg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(116, 88, '4th impeachment rap vs Sara Duterte transmitted to Speaker Dy’s office', 48, 'MANILA, Philippines — The fourth impeachment complaint against Vice President Sara Duterte has been transmitted to the Office of House of Representatives Speaker Faustino “Bojie” Dy III, the Office of the Secretary General said on Thursday.\r\n\r\nIn a statement, the office of House Secretary General Cheloy Garafil confirmed that the complaint filed by lawyer Nathaniel Cabrera, endorsed by Deputy Speaker Paolo Ortega and Manila Rep. Bienvenido Abante Jr., has already been received by Dy’s office.\r\n\r\nThis means four complaints are already pending before Dy, awaiting inclusion in the Order of Business.\r\n\r\n“A fourth impeachment complaint filed against Vice President Sara Duterte was formally received by the Office of the Secretary General at 6:34 p.m. on Wednesday and has been transmitted to the Office of Speaker Faustino ‘Bojie’ G. Dy III today, Thursday, in accordance with established House rules,” Garafil’s office said.\r\n\r\n“The verified complaint was filed by Atty. Nathaniel G. Cabrera and endorsed by House Committee on Human Rights Chair Bienvenido “Benny” Abante Jr. and Deputy Speaker Paolo Ortega V.  The OSG’s role is purely ministerial, confined to receiving and transmitting pleadings and documents filed with the House,” it added.', 1, 13, '2026-02-20 07:06:25', '2026-02-20 07:19:29', 3, 1, 'developing', 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_699807f1d3d08.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(117, 88, 'In Cebu, ‘impeach her’ call takes spotlight amid anti-dynasty talks', 98, 'MANILA, Philippines — Despite the program at the University of the Philippines (UP) Cebu City campus focusing on anti-political dynasty discussions, a resident’s call to impeach Vice President Sara Duterte stole the spotlight amid concerns that her 2028 presidential bid could weaken accountability.\r\n\r\nDuring the House of Representatives’ committee on suffrage and electoral reforms’ public consultation on Wednesday, private citizen R.A. Fortuna said:\r\n\r\n“First of all, allow me to request the members of Congress here: two words—Impeach her,” Fortuna said, drawing cheers from the crowd at UP Cebu.\r\n\r\n“I didn’t say ‘him,’ I said ‘her,’” he added.\r\n\r\nFortuna did not clarify who he was referring to, but currently, only one impeachable official has pending complaints before the House: Vice President Sara Duterte.\r\n\r\nAs of writing, four complaints against Duterte are lodged with House Speaker Faustino “Bojie” Dy III, citing alleged misuse of confidential funds in her offices, threats against ranking officials, and other possible violations of the 1987 Constitution.\r\n\r\nThe first two complaints from the Makabayan Coalition and civil society groups were filed on February 2. The third, from clergy members and lawyers, was submitted on February 9, while the fourth, from lawyer Nathaniel Cabrera, was forwarded to the House on February 18.', 1, 13, '2026-02-20 07:08:11', '2026-02-20 07:19:26', 3, 1, 'developing', 2, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_69980917ae32f2.78603284.jpeg', NULL, 'external_import', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(118, 106, 'Eala still a big winner with ranking points, cash earned despite Dubai exit', NULL, 'MANILA, Philippines — Filipina tennis ace Alex Eala has bowed out of the Dubai Duty Free Tennis Championships. \r\n\r\nBut surely, she will not be going home empty-handed. \r\n\r\nThe 20-year-old, World No. 47 tennister will be bringing home millions of pesos after her quarterfinal run in the WTA 1000 tournament. \r\n\r\nAccording to the Women’s Tennis Association (WTA) website, the tournament has a $4,088,211 prize money at stake. \r\n\r\nFor quarterfinalists, the prize money is at $98,500, or approximately P5.7 million. \r\n\r\nThose who were also booted out from the Last Eight — Antonia Ruzic, Clara Tauson and Mirra Andreeva — also brought home the same prize money. \r\n\r\nThis is double compared to the $49,250 to be takeb home by those who competed in the Round of 16.\r\n\r\nThe WTA said that semifinalists of the tournament will earn $197,000 (P11.4 million); the runner-up, $385,000 (P22.4 million); and the champion, $665,000 (P38.6 million). \r\n\r\nBut money is just one side of the coin for those competing in the tourney. \r\n\r\nEala also netted 215 ranking points after her quarterfinal exit.\r\n\r\nWith this, the Filipina is expected to reach a new career-high of World No. 32, according to the live WTA rankings.\r\n\r\nThis is the highest ranking for the 20-year-old, whose last career-high was No. 40.\r\n\r\nThe semifinalists will be awarded 390 points; the runner-up, 650 points; and the champion, a whopping 1,000 points.\r\n\r\nAfter her Middle East Swing, Eala will see action in the Indian Wells Open, which set to start March 4.\r\n\r\nShe is also listed in this year’s Miami Open, where she put the world on notice with huge wins last year.', 1, 12, '2026-02-20 07:11:21', '2026-02-20 07:19:23', 3, 1, 'developing', 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_699809192f5d0.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(119, 106, 'Eala bows to Gauff, crashes out of Dubai Tennis Championships', NULL, 'MANILA, Philippines — The spirited run of Alex Eala in the Dubai Duty Free Tennis Championships has ended. \r\n\r\nEala slammed into a brick wall that is World No. 4 Coco Gauff, 6-0, 6-2, in their quarterfinal round clash Thursday evening (Manila time). \r\n\r\nEala was at the receiving end of a dominant win by the American, who grabbed the victory in an hour and seven minutes.\r\n\r\n\"I was a bit better today. I could have served a little bit better, but I made it in when it mattered,\" Gauff said in the post-match interview.\r\n\r\n\"Alex is a tough competitor and even when I was up, I knew that she could come back at any given moment. I\'ve seen her do it before.\" \r\n\r\nThe Filipina was simply outmatched right from the get-go, yielding 15 unforced errors in the first set as she was bageled. \r\n\r\nGauff’s dominance continued on in the second set as she simply schooled the 20-year-old, much to Eala’s frustration. \r\n\r\nThe World No. 47 tennister finally put herself on the board in the fifth and sixth games of the second set to inch closer, 2-4, and she seemed to have found a second wind as the crowd continued trying to pump up the pride of the Philippines. \r\n\r\nBut Gauff found her groove anew, finishing off the match with wins in the seventh and eighth games. \r\n\r\nThe American punched in 29 service points to Eala\'s 14, while also winning 26 receiving points to her opponent\'s 19. \r\n\r\nAnd while Gauff had eight double faults, the Filipina had 33 unforced errors to her opponent\'s 19. \r\n\r\nBefore falling against the Florida native, Eala defeated Hailey Baptiste, 2024 tournament champion Jasmine Paolini, and battle-tested veteran Sorana Cirstea. \r\n\r\nGauff, for her part, will now face either World No. 67 Antonia Ruzic or World No. 9 Elina Svitolina in the semifinals. \r\n\r\nIn the other pairing, World No. 5 Jessica Pegula will take on World No. 6 Amanda Anisimova for a final berth. \r\n\r\nThe former defeated Clara Tauson in three sets, 6-3, 2-6, 6-4, while the latter dethroned defending champion Mirra Andreeva, 2-6, 7-5, 7-6(4).', 1, 12, '2026-02-20 07:14:34', '2026-02-20 07:19:15', 3, 1, 'developing', 2, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_699809da8b34f.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(120, 106, 'Gauff tips hat off to crowd-drawer Eala', NULL, 'MANILA, Philippines — World No. 4 tennister Coco Gauff lauded Alex Eala for “bringing a new demographic” to tennis, as the two faced off against each other before a rowdy crowd in the Dubai Duty Free Tennis Championships.\r\n\r\nGauff defeated Eala in dominating fashion, 6-0, 6-2, in their quarterfinal matchup late Thursday evening (Manila time).\r\n\r\nBut despite the score showing Eala being overpowered, the crowd did not make it seem that way.\r\n\r\nChants of “Let’s go Alex!” and “A-lex! A-lex!” showered center court, as they tried to rally the Filipina to a comeback victory that did not come.\r\n\r\nAfter the match, Gauff voiced appreciation to how the crowd cheered.\r\n\r\n“Yeah, thank you guys for coming out here, and I know you\'re mostly supporting Alex, but I have to say it is great to be on a crowded court,” she said during the post-match interview. \r\n\r\n“I played this tournament for many years and to see the stadium full that means a lot.” \r\n\r\nGauff, easily one of the most popular tennis players in the world, said that she also relished the cheers for her opponent.\r\n\r\n“I’d like to thank Alex for bringing a new demographic to the sport. I really appreciate it. I think it\'s great. I know sometimes it\'s tough when you\'re playing against a home crowd, but I think that it\'s great for the sport,” the 21-year-old American stressed. \r\n\r\n“So keep being enthusiastic and keep rooting for your player.”\r\n\r\nGauff added that when the crowd cheered for Eala, she just imagined that they are cheering her name.\r\n\r\n“Honestly, I had a similar match at French Open last year, so I brought that mindset today of just trying to whenever you guys were cheering for Alex I was pretending that it was my name and I think it helped me a lot,” she said. \r\n\r\n“If you can\'t beat them, you got to join them.” \r\n\r\nEala is one of the fastest rising stars in tennis today. \r\n\r\nAfter her miracle run in the Miami Open last year, she has competed against the best of the best, taking down numerous top 20 players.\r\n\r\nIn Dubai, she added former tournament champion Jasmine Paolini to her list after she defeated the Italian, 6-1, 7-6(5), in the Round of 32.\r\n\r\nAnd in every tournament she plays in, the Filipina brings crowds so rowdy that the umpire usually reminds the fans not to cheer during play. \r\n\r\nGauff will take on Elina Svitolina in the semifinal of the Dubai tourney.', 1, 12, '2026-02-20 07:16:02', '2026-02-20 07:19:12', 3, 1, 'developing', 3, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_69980a324e68b.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(121, NULL, 'P70 million illegal cigarettes seized in Pampanga', 50, 'MANILA, Philippines — Suspected illegaly manufactured cigarettes worth P70 million were seized on Monday following a raid in Pampanga on another warehouse, the fourth to be discovered by authorities this month.\r\n\r\nThe discovery of the warehouse in Barangay San Pablo Libutad in San Simon town was based on information provided by a concerned citizen, who notified police after having watched a press conference held by Interior and Local Government Secretary Jonvic Remulla about the raid on three illegal tobacco facilities.\r\n\r\nA few hours after the news conference, Philippine National Police chief Gen. Jose Melencio Nartatez Jr. said the PNP received a call from the informant, who told them about the existence of a similar facility in Golden Sun 999 Business Park.\r\n\r\nNartatez dispatched members of the police Criminal Detection and Investigation Group, who confirmed the presence of illicit cigarettes in the warehouse.\r\n\r\nThe raiding team seized 1,192 master cases of assorted cigarette brands.\r\n\r\nNo one was arrested in the raid.\r\n\r\nThe PNP has yet to confirm if the factory is related to three warehouses that were earlier discovered in San Simon, Mexico and San Fernando.\r\n\r\nThe raid on the warehouses on Feb. 11, 13 and 14 resulted in the seizure of P275 million worth of tobacco products and equipment used for manufacturing cigarettes.\r\n\r\nRemulla said two incumbent congressmen from Central Luzon are being investigated for being the alleged masterminds behind illegal cigarette factories in the country.\r\n\r\nHe declined to name the congressmen, citing case buildup still being conducted by police.\r\n\r\nThe congressmen have been placed under surveillance after a person linked to them attempted to bribe members of the Highway Patrol Group who seized tobacco products worth millions of pesos.\r\n\r\n“So far, that’s the only link we have on them, and we are not sure if this is sufficient to have them convicted in court,” Remulla said.\r\n\r\nThe congressmen reportedly tried to meet with Remulla through an emissary, but he rejected their request.\r\n\r\nP188 million seized cigarettes destroyed\r\nThe Bureau of Customs (BOC) on Monday destroyed 4,360 master cases of illicit cigarettes valued at P188 million, which were seized in separate operations in Northern Mindanao.\r\n\r\nThe contraband was destroyed at the compound of the Mindanao Container Terminal in Tagoloan, Misamis Oriental.\r\n\r\nThe ceremony was witnessed by BOC Deputy Commissioner Romeo Allan Rosales along with members of different law enforcement units as well as the military.\r\n\r\nRep. Yevgeny Vincente Emano of the second district of Misamis Oriental described the volume of confiscated contraband as unprecedented and among the largest in the country.\r\n\r\nRosales warned people and groups involved in the illicit cigarette trade noting the bureau would continue pursuing violators.\r\n\r\nThe destruction of the contraband was part of the celebration of the BOC’s 50th anniversary.', 1, 12, '2026-02-20 07:18:22', '2026-02-20 07:19:08', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_69980abe5a5b02.89363137.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(122, 121, 'Remulla: Illegal cigarettes smugglers have ‘backers’ in government', 50, 'MANILA, Philippines — The Department of Interior and Local Government (DILG) is preparing charges against an alleged smuggler of illicit cigarettes, but agency secretary Jonvic Remulla says that these illegal operations are likely backed by government officials.  \r\n\r\nThe DILG has raided an illegal warehouse owned by a certain Jimmy Reyes Cua in Tanza, Cavite.\r\n\r\nDespite being declared as a canned goods storage site, citizens in the area reported a tobacco odor from the warehouse. \r\n\r\nAuthorities raised the warehouse, finding cigarette manufacturing machinery, industrial generators, and other equipment.\r\n\r\nThis is the fifth warehouse in a series of government raids against tobacco smugglers, with Remulla eyeing 10 major raids in total. \r\n\r\nThe DILG is preparing raps against the suspects for allegedly violating the Customs Modernization and Tariff Act, as well as the Anti-Agricultural Economic Sabotage Act.\r\n\r\n“Imposible na mangyari ito na walang protector. Sigurado ako na merong tao sa gobyerno na nasa taas lahat ito, at hindi kami titigil hanggang makuha namin at matigil namin lahat operasyon nila,” Remulla said in a press briefing on Friday, February 20. \r\n\r\n(It is impossible for this to happen without a protector. I am sure that there are people in the government high up there, and we will not stop until we get them and stop all of their operations.)   \r\n\r\nRemulla said that once these smugglers are charged, they will coordinate with the Anti-Money Laundering Council to trace the finances and see if they are tied to more powerful people. \r\n\r\nAside from being backed by officials, Remulla said that many of the warehouses and illegal factories that police have raided are owned by Chinese nationals. All of their machines are also from Mainland China.', 1, 12, '2026-02-20 07:19:24', '2026-02-23 03:52:01', 3, 1, 'developing', 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_69980afcc97e0.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(124, NULL, 'Refurbished vs. New Phones in 2026: Finding the Perfect Balance Between Cost and Features', 54, 'As smartphone prices continue to soar, the decision between purchasing a new or refurbished phone has become increasingly crucial in 2026. While new phones boast the latest features and full battery life, refurbished models present a compelling value proposition, delivering similar performance at a significantly lower cost.\r\n\r\nWhen it comes to hardware performance, advancements in technology have made even older flagship devices still feel powerful and modern. Processors, RAM, and storage capacities have improved to the point where a refurbished two-year-old high-end phone can often outperform the current mid-range offerings. This means that for many users, the performance gap between new and refurbished phones has narrowed considerably, reducing the need to pay premium prices for the newest releases.\r\n\r\nCamera quality is another area where refurbished phones have become increasingly competitive. Smartphone cameras have advanced rapidly in recent years, and even the cameras on older flagship devices can capture stunning photos and videos. While the latest computational photography features may be missing, the core imaging hardware on many refurbished phones is still more than capable of meeting the needs of most users.\r\n\r\nSoftware updates are often a concern when considering a refurbished phone, as older devices may not receive the same level of long-term support as their newer counterparts. However, the software landscape has also evolved, with many Android manufacturers and even Apple providing extended update periods for their devices. Additionally, the rise of custom ROM communities and third-party software support has made it possible to keep even older phones feeling fresh and secure.\r\n\r\nSustainability is an increasingly important factor in consumer decisions, and refurbished phones offer a more eco-friendly alternative to purchasing brand-new devices. By giving new life to existing hardware, refurbished phones reduce electronic waste and minimize the environmental impact of smartphone production and disposal.\r\n\r\nUltimately, for the majority of buyers in 2026, refurbished phones make the most sense, offering an excellent balance of cost and features. However, new phones still have their place for those who prioritize the latest hardware, maximum battery life, and long-term ownership. The decision ultimately comes down to individual needs, usage patterns, and budget, with both new and refurbished options providing viable choices in the evolving smartphone market.', 1, 4, '2026-02-20 08:13:23', '2026-02-23 03:51:58', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_699817a30dbf70.98396309.png', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(126, NULL, 'Empowering Filipinos through Food Label Literacy: Insights from the Philippine Association of Nutrition', 53, 'In today\'s increasingly complex food landscape, understanding food labels has become a critical skill for Filipino consumers. As emphasized by the Philippine Association of Nutrition (PAN), food labels are more than just regulatory compliance – they are powerful tools that empower individuals to align their food choices with their personal health goals and lifestyle needs.\r\n\r\nThe importance of clear and transparent labeling is highlighted, as it builds consumer trust and facilitates understanding. When food labels provide clear and accurate information, consumers can make informed decisions that support their well-being. This is particularly important in a country like the Philippines, where the prevalence of non-communicable diseases, such as diabetes and cardiovascular disease, continues to rise.\r\n\r\nHowever, the responsibility does not lie solely with the food industry. The article stresses the importance of consumers cultivating nutrition literacy, which allows them to critically evaluate claims, compare nutritional values, and make healthier decisions, especially for their families. By understanding the information on food labels, Filipinos can make informed choices that prioritize their health and well-being.\r\n\r\nWhile understanding labels is crucial, the enduring principles of balance and moderation in achieving a healthy diet are also reiterated. Filipinos are encouraged to start with simple habits, such as consistently checking the serving size and nutrition facts panel, to kickstart their journey towards better-informed and healthier food choices. These small steps can have a significant impact on an individual\'s overall health and can contribute to the broader societal goal of improving the nation\'s health outcomes.\r\n\r\nThe message is clear: food label literacy empowers Filipinos to take control of their health and well-being, one informed choice at a time. By equipping consumers with the knowledge and skills to interpret food labels, the Philippine Association of Nutrition is empowering Filipinos to make more mindful and nutritious choices, ultimately contributing to a healthier and more sustainable future for the nation.', 1, 4, '2026-02-20 08:43:15', '2026-02-23 03:51:56', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_69981ea391c0d4.45280130.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(127, NULL, 'Meta Shifts Focus to Mobile-First Metaverse Strategy', 92, 'When Facebook rebranded to Meta in 2021, it signaled the company\'s strong belief in the future of virtual reality (VR) technology. A key part of this vision was Horizon Worlds, which Meta envisioned as the primary way people would communicate in the metaverse.\r\n\r\nHowever, it appears that the VR fad may be fading, and Meta is now pivoting to a mobile-first approach for its metaverse ambitions. In a recent interview, Samantha Ryan, Meta\'s VP of Content at Reality Labs, revealed that Horizon Worlds is shifting gears to become \"almost exclusively mobile.\"\r\n\r\nAs part of this change, Meta is splitting Horizon Worlds and the Quest VR platform into two separate products. On the Quest or VR side, the focus will be on supporting third-party developers and content, rather than first-party worlds. In fact, individual Horizon Worlds destinations are being pulled from the VR store, and the Worlds section is disappearing from the Quest home screen.\r\n\r\nOn the Horizon side, the focus is almost entirely shifting to mobile. According to Meta, in 2025, the number of mobile-only Horizon Worlds grew from zero to 2,000, and the number of monthly users increased more than four times. To support this mobile-first strategy, Meta is introducing and expanding the availability of new tools, such as the Meta Horizon Studio and the Meta Horizon Engine, to help create more engaging mobile worlds. Additionally, Meta is introducing new monetization tools, like featured bundles and season passes.\r\n\r\nThis shift in strategy raises questions about Meta\'s ability to compete with established players in the mobile gaming and virtual world space, such as Roblox and Fortnite. While Meta\'s mobile-first approach may be a sensible move, the restructuring has not been without its challenges. Recently, the company\'s Reality Labs division, which is responsible for the development of VR and metaverse technologies, laid off around 10% of its workforce.\r\n\r\nThe metaverse is a rapidly evolving and highly competitive landscape, and Meta\'s decision to pivot to a mobile-first strategy reflects the changing priorities and realities of the industry. As the company continues to navigate this transition, it will be crucial for them to maintain a strong focus on user engagement, content creation, and monetization to stay relevant and competitive in the rapidly evolving world of virtual experiences.', 1, 4, '2026-02-23 02:43:20', '2026-02-23 03:51:53', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_699bbec81dace8.18502949.png', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(129, NULL, 'Navigating the Evolving AI Startup Landscape: Challenges for Wrappers and Aggregators', 54, 'The AI startup ecosystem is rapidly evolving, and according to a recent warning from a Google executive, two popular types of AI startups could be in trouble - wrappers and aggregators.\r\n\r\nDarren Mowry, who heads Google\'s global startup organization, told TechCrunch that companies built around large language model (LLM) wrappers and AI aggregators may be facing headwinds. Wrappers are startups that take existing LLMs like ChatGPT and build a product or consumer-facing layer on top, while aggregators pull multiple LLMs into a single interface or API.\r\n\r\nMowry\'s assessment is that the market is growing wary of these types of startups. For wrappers, he argues that simply \"white-labeling\" an underlying model without adding significant differentiation is no longer enough. \"If you\'re really just counting on the back-end model to do all the work and you\'re almost white-labeling that model, the industry doesn\'t have a lot of patience for that anymore,\" Mowry said. \r\n\r\nHe emphasizes that startups need to build \"deep, wide moats\" through either horizontal differentiation or vertical market specialization to stand out. Mere wrappers are unlikely to progress and grow in the current environment.\r\n\r\nAI aggregators face their own challenges. While many have found success in giving users access to multiple models through a unified interface, Mowry believes they too need to add more \"intellectual property\" to steer users to the right model at the right time. Users, he says, want to see AI startups build something proprietary into the experience.\r\n\r\nThese warnings come as the broader AI landscape continues to evolve rapidly. A recent PYMNTS report examines how agentic AI is reconfiguring the B2B product experience. In this new paradigm, the digital shelf is no longer just about merchandising - it\'s a complex data engineering challenge, especially for online marketplaces.\r\n\r\nAgentic commerce, where AI drives procurement decisions, collapses the traditional separation between sourcing, contracting, and settlement. Factors like payment terms, credit availability, and settlement speed now become critical inputs to purchasing algorithms. \r\n\r\nAs a result, PYMNTS argues that \"if aggregation defined the first generation of B2B marketplaces and workflow defined the second, payments and data structure are emerging as the connective tissue of the landscape\'s agentic-driven third act.\"\r\n\r\nThe clear message is that the AI startup world is evolving rapidly, and simple wrappers or aggregators may no longer be enough. Startups need to build deep, differentiated intellectual property and integrate seamlessly with the new agentic commerce landscape. Those that can\'t may find themselves facing an ominous \"check engine\" light, as Mowry warned.', 1, 4, '2026-02-23 02:59:57', '2026-02-23 03:51:50', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_699bc2adb60af1.48443736.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(131, NULL, 'Engineered Algae: A Revolutionary Solution to Microplastics Pollution', 54, 'University Researcher Pioneers Innovative Algae-Based Technology to Remove Microplastics from Water\r\n\r\nProfessor Susie Dai of the University of Missouri has developed a groundbreaking genetic engineering technique to create a new strain of algae that can effectively remove microplastics from wastewater. This innovative solution holds the potential to tackle the growing problem of microplastics pollution in the Philippines and beyond.\r\n\r\nMicroplastics, defined as plastic particles less than 5 millimeters in size, have become a pervasive environmental concern, with studies detecting their presence in air, water, and even the human food chain. These tiny plastic fragments can disrupt hormones, leading to potential reproductive issues, metabolic disorders, and respiratory problems.\r\n\r\nThe Philippines, as the world\'s top source of plastic waste in the oceans, faces a particularly severe microplastics pollution challenge. Studies on Laguna Lake have revealed widespread contamination, with particles from single-use plastics and disposable masks entering human bodies through ingestion and inhalation.\r\n\r\nProfessor Dai\'s research aims to address this problem head-on. By genetically engineering a new strain of algae, she has created a water-repellent organism that can effectively capture and remove microplastics from wastewater. The key lies in the algae\'s production of a natural oil called limonene, which attracts the water-repellent microplastics, causing them to clump together and sink to the bottom for easy collection and removal.\r\n\r\nThe specially engineered algae can thrive in wastewater, feeding on excess nutrients and cleaning the water as it grows. This innovative approach tackles multiple issues simultaneously: removing microplastics, cleaning wastewater, and potentially repurposing the collected microplastics into bioplastic products.\r\n\r\nDai envisions integrating this new algae-based process into existing wastewater treatment plants, enabling cities to clean their water more effectively and reduce pollution while creating useful products. The research, published in the journal Nature Communications, is still in the early stages, but Dai is working to scale up the technology and make it more widely applicable.\r\n\r\nBy harnessing the power of genetic engineering and the natural properties of algae, Professor Dai\'s groundbreaking work offers a promising solution to the growing microplastics crisis. As the Philippines and the world grapple with the environmental and health impacts of these pervasive pollutants, this innovative algae-based technology could pave the way for a cleaner and more sustainable future.', 1, 4, '2026-02-23 03:40:35', '2026-02-23 03:51:46', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_699bcce77108a5.65004455.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(133, NULL, 'AFP Enhances Interagency Collaboration with Training in Tarlac', 46, 'In a significant effort to enhance operational efficiency and interagency collaboration, the Armed Forces of the Philippines (AFP) conducted an interagency coordination training in Tarlac. This initiative, aimed at improving the capacity of various government agencies to respond effectively to national security challenges, was held at the AFP Command and General Staff College. The training brought together representatives from multiple sectors, including law enforcement, disaster response, and local government units, highlighting the importance of a unified approach in addressing complex situations.\r\n\r\nThe training program included a series of workshops and simulations designed to foster communication and coordination among participating agencies. Facilitators emphasized the critical need for a cohesive response framework, particularly in crisis situations where timely and effective action is paramount. Participants engaged in practical exercises that tested their abilities to work collaboratively, share resources, and leverage each other\'s strengths. This focused approach not only aimed to improve individual agency capabilities but also sought to establish a network of cooperation that can be activated during emergencies.\r\n\r\nOfficials from the AFP underscored the importance of such training in building resilience within communities and enhancing national security protocols. By fostering strong interagency relationships, the AFP aims to create a more robust response system capable of addressing a wide range of threats, from natural disasters to security concerns. As the complexities of modern challenges evolve, the need for integrated strategies becomes increasingly vital, making initiatives like the Tarlac training a crucial component of the AFP\'s ongoing commitment to national safety and security.', 1, 10, '2026-02-23 06:09:22', '2026-02-23 06:42:05', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_699bef120bd703.63944006.jpeg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(134, NULL, 'Philippines Faces Challenges in Achieving Digital Payments Targets, Warns BSP', 54, 'The Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas (BSP) has raised concerns regarding the Philippines\' potential to meet its ambitious digital payments targets. The central bank had previously set a goal to transition 50% of all retail transactions to digital formats by 2023 as part of its broader strategy to enhance financial inclusion across the nation. However, recent evaluations suggest that the country may fall short of this target, highlighting several underlying issues that need to be addressed.\r\n\r\nOne of the primary challenges hindering the growth of digital payments in the Philippines is the lack of infrastructure, particularly in rural areas. While urban centers have seen a surge in digital payment adoption, many remote locations still rely heavily on cash transactions due to limited internet access and inadequate financial services. The BSP has emphasized the need for improved connectivity and infrastructure investments to bridge this digital divide. Additionally, the disparity in financial literacy among the population poses another significant barrier, as many individuals remain unaware of the advantages and operations of digital payment systems.\r\n\r\nTo overcome these obstacles, the BSP is actively working to promote financial education and encourage the adoption of digital platforms among both businesses and consumers. Initiatives such as partnerships with private sector stakeholders and public awareness campaigns aim to foster a culture of digital payments, emphasizing not only convenience but also security and efficiency. The BSP\'s commitment to supporting a more inclusive financial ecosystem is crucial, especially in light of the ongoing push for economic recovery post-pandemic. As the country navigates these challenges, collaborative efforts will be essential in realizing the full potential of digital payments and achieving the targeted transformation in the financial landscape of the Philippines.', 1, 10, '2026-02-23 06:15:17', '2026-02-23 06:42:02', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_699bf07538f736.89496404.jpeg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(135, NULL, 'When Cultures Connect: Pinoy Customs Drive Sari-Sari Store Sales for Chinese New Year', 49, 'The vibrant spirit of Filipino communal celebration, often seen during traditional holidays, is now extending its reach to an unlikely calendar event: Chinese New Year. Despite being designated a special non-working holiday rather than a regular one, the festive atmosphere surrounding the Lunar New Year has proven to be a significant boon for the Philippines\' ubiquitous sari-sari stores. Data from Packworks, a leading retail-tech startup, reveals a compelling trend: a surge in sales driven by distinctly Pinoy traditions of gathering, feasting, and last-minute preparations.\r\n\r\nAccording to Packworks\' comprehensive analysis, sari-sari stores across the archipelago experienced an average sales increase of 15% during the Chinese New Year week compared to the preceding week. This impressive growth underscores the deep-rooted Filipino inclination to celebrate, regardless of a holiday\'s official status. The impact was particularly pronounced in key provinces, with Laguna, Pampanga, Cavite, Batangas, and Bulacan reporting even higher jumps, ranging from 18% to 20%. Other regions, including Bicol, Western Visayas, and Zamboanga Peninsula, also witnessed double-digit sales growth, painting a picture of nationwide participation in the festivities. The types of products flying off the shelves further solidify the narrative of communal celebration: carbonated drinks, instant noodles, beer, chips, and a variety of snacks topped the sales charts – all essential ingredients for impromptu gatherings and family meals.\r\n\r\nThis phenomenon highlights the crucial role sari-sari stores play within Filipino communities. Often the most accessible retail points, especially in remote areas, these micro-enterprises become indispensable hubs for last-minute purchases and daily necessities. The sales surge during Chinese New Year is', 1, 10, '2026-02-23 06:21:44', '2026-02-23 06:41:58', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_699bf1f8ce5ab8.23011968.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(136, NULL, 'Headline: Manila Police Under Investigation for Allegedly Blocking Driver at Traffic Light', 50, 'The National Police Commission (Napolcom) is investigating some Manila Police District (MPD) officers after a video emerged showing an MPD vehicle allegedly blocking a driver at a traffic light while it was on a go signal.\r\n\r\nThe incident, which occurred along Taft Avenue near the Philippine General Hospital in Ermita, was captured in a video shared by vlogger James Deakin on social media. The video, which was provided to Deakin by the wife of the driver involved, shows the MPD vehicle suddenly cutting off the driver\'s vehicle, causing the driver to honk their horn to alert the officers.\r\n\r\nNapolcom Executive Officer Rafael Calinisan expressed his disappointment in the officers\' actions, stating, \"I am not exactly thrilled with what I saw.\" He immediately contacted the district director of the Manila Police District and instructed him to have the officers involved report to the Napolcom office for an investigation.\r\n\r\nCalinisan noted that he has yet to determine the exact number of police officers in the vehicle, but he described the incident as \"very petty\" and emphasized that such actions should not occur within the police force. He added, \"That kind of action should not happen in our police force... Hotter heads prevailed.\"\r\n\r\nThe driver\'s wife, who shared the video with Deakin, questioned whether citizens can no longer honk their horns at police vehicles on the road, and whether it is appropriate for a police car to retaliate in such a manner. She argued that the police should be role models on the roads, not those who set a bad example.\r\n\r\nThe Napolcom\'s motu proprio investigation is aimed at addressing this incident and ensuring that the police officers involved are held accountable for their actions, which appear to have violated the standards of professional conduct expected from law enforcement personnel.', 1, 4, '2026-02-23 06:21:53', '2026-02-23 06:41:55', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_699bf201232c04.03512494.webp', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(137, NULL, 'NASA to Roll Back Artemis II Rocket Following Helium Supply Issue', 54, 'NASA is set to roll back the Artemis II rocket from its launch pad on February 24 due to a significant helium supply issue that has arisen during preparations for the much-anticipated mission. This decision comes as part of the agency\'s commitment to ensuring the safety and integrity of the spacecraft before it embarks on its historic journey to the Moon. The Artemis II mission aims to carry astronauts around the lunar orbit, marking a pivotal step in NASA’s broader Artemis program, which seeks to establish a sustainable human presence on the Moon and eventually pave the way for human exploration of Mars.\r\n\r\nThe helium issue was identified during recent checks, raising concerns about the rocket\'s readiness for launch. Helium is a critical component used in various systems of the Space Launch System (SLS), particularly for pressurizing fuel tanks and ensuring the stability of the spacecraft during its ascent. NASA engineers are working diligently to address the situation, but the agency has opted for a cautious approach by returning the rocket to the Vehicle Assembly Building (VAB) for further inspection and necessary repairs. This decision reflects NASA’s stringent safety protocols, ensuring that all systems are functioning optimally before the rocket is cleared for launch.\r\n\r\nThe Artemis II mission is particularly significant as it will be the first crewed flight in the Artemis program, intended to demonstrate critical technologies and operations needed for future lunar exploration. Originally scheduled for launch in late 2024, delays caused by the helium issue may push timelines further, emphasizing the complexities of space exploration. As NASA navigates these challenges, they remain committed to transparency, providing regular updates to the public and stakeholders. The agency aims to inspire confidence in the Artemis program, showcasing its dedication not only to innovation but also to safety and thoroughness in its pursuit of new frontiers in space.', 1, 10, '2026-02-23 06:39:32', '2026-02-23 06:41:51', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_699bf624b749c2.96330971.jpg', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(138, NULL, 'PayPal Customers Impacted by Data Breach, Passwords Reset', 50, 'PayPal has confirmed a data breach that exposed personal information of some of its users for around six months. The breach impacted the company\'s PayPal Working Capital (PPWC) loan application process, allowing a hacker to gain unauthorized access to PayPal\'s systems from July to December 2025.\r\n\r\nThe exposed information includes names, email addresses, phone numbers, business addresses, Social Security numbers, and dates of birth. A small number of customers, around 100 according to PayPal, also experienced unauthorized transactions on their accounts, which have been refunded.\r\n\r\nPayPal has terminated the attacker\'s access to its systems and reset the passwords of affected accounts. The company is offering two years of complimentary credit monitoring and identity restoration services to those impacted.\r\n\r\nTo protect themselves, PayPal is advising all users to use unique username and password combinations, change passwords and security questions if they detect suspicious activity, be wary of phishing attempts, and never provide login credentials over a call, text, or email. The article also recommends using passkeys whenever available for added security.\r\n\r\nWhile the breach appears to have been limited in scope, it serves as a reminder for all PayPal customers to remain vigilant and take proactive steps to safeguard their accounts and personal information.', 1, 4, '2026-02-23 06:47:43', '2026-02-23 07:42:52', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_699bf80f3dd984.64774320.webp', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0),
(139, NULL, 'Mayweather\'s Return Sparks Pacquiao Rematch Talk', 56, 'Filipino boxing icon Manny Pacquiao has recently teased the possibility of a rematch with Floyd Mayweather Jr., sparked by Mayweather’s announcement of his return to the boxing ring. At a press event for the partnership between Sportsplus and the Maharlika Pilipinas Basketball League (MPBL), Pacquiao was asked about Mayweather\'s decision to come out of retirement. He cryptically replied, \"Abangan niyo na lang announcement\" (Just wait for the announcement), leaving fans speculating on what could unfold. Mayweather, who retired in 2017 with an impressive record of 50 wins and no losses, has remained active through various exhibition bouts. His next challenge is set against former heavyweight champion Mike Tyson on April 25, paving the way for a potential return to professional boxing. Meanwhile, Pacquiao is also preparing for his own exhibition match against former world champion Ruslan Provodnikov on April 18 in Las Vegas.\r\n\r\nThe first encounter between these two boxing titans, known as the \"Fight of the Century,\" took place in 2015, where Mayweather claimed victory by unanimous decision. Since then, the idea of a rematch has captivated fans and analysts alike. Pacquiao’s return to the ring occurred approximately seven months ago, when he fought Mario Barrios Jr. to a draw. Following Mayweather\'s recent statements, Pacquiao has expressed that a rematch is among the options he is considering for his next bout. In addition to his boxing endeavors, he is committed to maintaining the integrity of the MPBL, especially in light of ongoing game-fixing allegations. \"As the founder of the Maharlika Pilipinas Basketball League, I am always watching to protect the integrity and the name of the MPBL,\" Pacquiao declared, urging players to stay clear of any misconduct that could threaten their careers. \"We can play the game fairly and show it to the public. Getting involved in that will only destroy your integrity as players,\" he asserted. With both fighters gearing up for their upcoming events, the boxing world eagerly anticipates further updates on a potential rematch that could once again captivate audiences globally.', 1, 8, '2026-02-23 07:06:27', '2026-02-23 07:42:48', 3, 0, NULL, 1, NULL, 'uploads/thumb_699bfc73e6a184.25002727.webp', NULL, 'manual', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0);
