(156, 88, NULL, 'Sara Duterte, tatakbong presidente sa 2028', 'Inanunsyo ni Bise Presidente Sara Duterte nitong Miyerkoles na tatakbo siyang presidente sa 2028 national elections. \"Ako si Sara Duterte tatakbo bilang pangulo ng Pilipinas,” sabi ni Duterte sa isang punong balitaan. Bago ang punong balitaan, iniutos ni Duterte ang pagtanggal ng logo ng Office of the Vice President sa podium. Hindi siya sumagot sa anumang tanong mula sa mga reporter pagkatapos ng kaniyang talumpati. Sinabi niya na inaako niya ang buong responsibilidad para sa kaniyang mga desisyon sa politika at kinilala ang pagkadismaya ng publiko sa mga isyung pambansa. “Mga kababayan, humihingi ako ng paumanhin sa inyong lahat. Patawad kung tinulungan kong mahalal si BBM bilang Pangulo ng ating bansa,” sabi niya. Sinabi ng Pangalawang Pangulo na bigo si Pangulong Ferdinand \"Bongbong\" Marcos Jr. na tuparin ang mga pangako sa kampanya at sinumpaang tungkulin. Sinabi rin ni Duterte na nagbitiw siya sa kaniyang posisyon sa Gabinete matapos magdesisyong hindi niya masusuportahan ang pambansang badyet para sa 2025 na inilarawan niyang \"tainted with corruption.\" Sinabi niyang inaasahan na niyang hahantong sa impeachment ang kaniyang pagbibitiw bilang kalihim ng Department of Education. “Dahil hindi ko kinayang maging bahagi ng 2025 national budget na tadtad ng katiwalian, pinili kong umalis sa Gabinete,” sabi niya. Sinabi ni Duterte na sa mga unang buwan pa lamang ng administrasyon, sinimulan na niyang kuwestiyonin ang inilarawan niyang kawalan ng integridad sa pamamahala. Sa limang-pahinang talumpati, inilista ni Duterte ang tinatawag niyang mga kabiguan ng administrasyon: patuloy na pagbaha, pagtaas ng presyo ng mga pangunahing bilihin, kawalan ng seguridad sa pagkain, mahinang sistema ng pangangalagang pangkalusugan, pagguho ng imprastraktura, at ang patuloy na krimen, ilegal na droga, at terorismo. Binatikos din niya ang inilarawan niya bilang kawalan ng malinaw at malayang foreign policy, at sinabi niyang nanganganib ang bansa na maipit sa pagitan ng mga pandaigdigang superpower. “Patuloy ang pagtaas ng presyo ng mga pangunahing bilihin habang nananatiling kapos ang kita ng bawat pamilya,” sabi niya. Iginiit pa ni Duterte na layunin ng mga imbestigasyon na may motibong politika at paulit-ulit na mga akusasyon na sirain ang kaniyang reputasyon, kabilang ang inilarawan niya bilang \"scripted\" na congressional inquiries. “Matagal na akong inaatake gamit ang buong makinarya ng kapangyarihan,” sabi niya. Bagama\'t sinabi niyang hindi siya natatakot para sa sarili, nagpahayag naman ng pagmamalasakit si Duterte para sa kinabukasan ng bansa, lalo na para sa mga nakababatang henerasyon. “May takot ako para sa ating mga anak. May takot ako para sa mga susunod na henerasyon,” sabi niya. Sinabi ni Duterte na ang kaniyang kandidatura ay isang pag-aalok ng serbisyo imbes na pagkuha ng simpatiya. “I cannot kneel before each and every Filipino to beg for forgiveness. Instead, I offer my life, my strength, and my future in the service of our nation,” sabi niya. —VBL GMA Integrated News\r\n\r\n---\r\nAuthor: GMA News\r\nSource: GMA News\r\nPublished: February 18, 2026', 48, 1, 12, 'uploads/thumb_699549d9bfc0e9.96445824.jpg', NULL, NULL, 'manual', 1, 0, NULL, 1, '2026-02-18 05:48:25', '2026-02-18 05:48:25', '2026-02-18 13:48:25', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'normal', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(157, 97, 132, 'Cantada lifts Lady Bulldogs past Lady Falcons', 'MANILA, Philippines — In a battle of young volleyball rising stars, Sam Cantada reigned supreme for the National University Lady Bulldogs.\r\n\r\nCantada carried the load for the three-peat-seeking Lady Bulldogs side as they swept the Shaina Nitura-led Adamson Lady Falcons, 25-23, 25-19, 28-26, in their UAAP Season 88 women’s volleyball clash Wednesday at the UST Quadricentennial Pavilion in Manila.\r\n\r\nThe 18-year-old former Juniors Most Valuable Player finished with 16 points on 13 attacks, two aces and a block. She also had nine excellent receptions against her former high school teammate Nitura. Arah Panique chipped in 13 markers on nine attacks and four blocks.\r\n\r\n“Yes po [natagtag ko na ang pressure.] Mas kumpiyansa na rin po ako lalo na sa crucial game po, mas nalalaban ko po siya. Nawawala po yung bigat sa dibdib ko,” Cantada told reporters after the match.\r\n\r\nThe two teams were kept in a tight third set, with neither gaining significant advantage.\r\n\r\nA Frances Mordi attack tied things up at 23-all.\r\n\r\nA Princess Dote block on Cantada pushed the Lady Falcons ahead, 24-23, before a checkball by the young NU star tied things up anew.\r\n\r\nNitura then gave Adamson the set point, 25-24, but it was quickly taken back by a service error by Dote.\r\n\r\nPanique and Nitura traded late attacks, before the Adamson star’s save went out, giving NU a 27-26 lead.\r\n\r\nAlexa Mata then iced the match with a service ace to help the Lady Bulldogs stamp their second win in an hour and 31 minutes. \r\n\r\nThe reigning UAAP MVP Nitura produced 18 points for Adamson, all from attacks. Frances Mordi backstopped with 17. \r\n\r\nFacing off against her former juniors team, Cantada said that she made sure to just focus on what’s in front of her.\r\n\r\n“Game is game na po. Like past na yun, tapos na po yun, and alam ko po ngayon okay na rin sila doon and okay na rin ako dito.” \r\n\r\nNU is now holding a 2-0 win-loss record in the season. \r\n\r\nAdamson dropped to 1-1.\r\n\r\nThe Lady Bulldogs will try to keep it going as they take on the Far Eastern University Lady Tamaraws, while the Lady Falcons will seek to return to its winning ways against University of the East Lady Warriors. Both games are on Saturday at the Mall of Asia Arena.', 56, 1, 13, 'uploads/thumb_69955d7e2b8392.21981673.jpg', NULL, NULL, 'manual', 1, 1, 'developing', 1, '2026-02-18 06:57:39', '2026-02-18 06:57:39', '2026-02-18 14:57:39', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'normal', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(158, 96, NULL, 'Bam Aquino: EJK cases should be tried in PH courts', 'Senator Bam Aquino on Tuesday said cases against individuals implicated in alleged extrajudicial killings during the Duterte administration’s drug war should be tried in Philippine courts rather than before an international tribunal.\r\n\r\nAquino made the statement after the International Criminal Court Office of the Prosecutor identified Senators Bong Go and Ronald “Bato” dela Rosa as among the alleged co-perpetrators in the crimes against humanity case against former president Rodrigo Duterte.\r\n\r\nSpeaking in an interview on Unang Balita, Aquino said the Philippines must confront the killings that occurred and pursue justice locally, noting that the victims and their families are in the country.\r\n\r\n“The trials for these cases should ideally be held here in the Philippines because this is where the victims are,” Aquino said, adding that seeking justice where the alleged crimes happened would be more meaningful.\r\n\r\nPalace to Rodrigo Duterte\'s \'co-perpetrators\': Don’t hide if you’re innocent\r\nFormer Justice chief Aguirre denies involvement in Duterte’s drug war\r\nICC: No confirmation yet on Dela Rosa warrant\r\nDespite this, Aquino said he respects the ongoing process at the ICC, which is based in The Hague.\r\n\r\nHe added that senators are expected to discuss the matter involving Go and dela Rosa in a caucus, but emphasized the need to wait for the court’s formal actions before drawing conclusions.\r\n\r\nThe confirmation of charges in Duterte’s case is scheduled to begin on February 23, with subsequent hearings set for February 24, 26, and 27.', 48, 1, 13, 'uploads/thumb_69955c141fabe8.71249341.jpg', NULL, NULL, 'manual', 1, 0, NULL, 1, '2026-02-18 06:57:43', '2026-02-18 06:57:43', '2026-02-18 14:57:43', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'normal', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(159, 94, NULL, 'Couple, helper charged with murder of cop, son', 'MANILA, Philippines — The Quezon City police have filed murder charges against a car agent, her husband, and their helper for allegedly killing Police Senior Master Sgt. Diane Marie Mollenido and her son, 8-year-old John Ysmael, over a car deal scam.\r\n\r\n“The suspects, identified as Christian [Panganiban], Pia Katrina [Panganiban], and Gil [Dy Jr.], have been formally charged with two counts of murder, with no bail recommended, after the investigating prosecutor [found] prima facie evidence with a reasonable certainty of conviction against them,” the Quezon City Police District (QCPD) said in a statement on Tuesday.\r\n\r\n“In addition, Maribel [Panganiban], who was initially named as a suspect, has been cleared of all charges and will now be treated as an ordinary witness,” the QCPD added.\r\n\r\nMaribel is the sister of Christian Panganiban, a dismissed policeman. She and Dy were earlier suspected of having helped the couple clean up the crime scene.', 47, 1, 12, 'uploads/thumb_6995537985aba4.12400254.jpg', NULL, NULL, 'manual', 1, 0, NULL, 1, '2026-02-18 06:57:47', '2026-02-18 06:57:47', '2026-02-18 14:57:47', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'normal', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(160, 106, NULL, 'Alex Eala ousts Cirstea, sets up quarterfinal duel vs Coco Gauff', 'MANILA, Philippines–Alex Eala took down higher-ranked Sorana Cirstea of Romania, 7-5, 6-4, early Thursday (Manila time) to book her spot in the quarterfinals of the Dubai Tennis Championships.\r\n\r\nEala put on another impressive showing in the nightcap at Center Court, racing to a 5-1 lead in the second set before sealing her second quarterfinal appearance of the Middle East swing in front of another big Filipino crowd.\r\n\r\n“Every round is such a battle and so filled with tension. So I’m really happy with how I performed,” Eala said in the post-match interview.\r\n\r\n“I think the key to today was staying calm and trusting my shots. I think I was very solid in particular moments where I needed to be. So that reflected in my performance and in the score.”\r\n\r\nThe Filipino tennis ace avenged a three-set loss to Cirstea at the 2024 Mutua Madrid Open.\r\n\r\nThis time, Eala kept Cirstea from finding her rhythm, especially in the first set when the World No. 32 took a 5-4 lead.\r\n\r\nEala responded by rattling off three straight games and carried the momentum into the second set with four consecutive games for a 4-0 lead.\r\n\r\nCirstea, who is retiring from tennis after the 2026 season, pulled within 5-4, but Eala held at love in the 10th game to end the match.\r\n\r\nEala, who 24 hours earlier eliminated No. 8 Jasmine Paolini, will face two-time Grand Slam champion Coco Gauff in the quarterfinals later on Thursday.\r\n\r\n“I think I’m in a good path. I think if I continue like this, the next match will be great,” Eala said. “Coco [Gauff] is such an amazing person. We tend to forget that she’s just a year older than me. But she’s a great role model for so many.”\r\n\r\nGauff outlasted Elise Mertens, 2-6, 7-6(9), 6-3, shortly before Eala’s round-of-16 match, securing her entry into the next round.', NULL, 1, 12, 'uploads/thumb_699686617794d6.10482183.png', NULL, NULL, 'manual', 1, 0, NULL, 1, '2026-02-19 03:43:13', '2026-02-19 03:43:13', '2026-02-19 11:43:13', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'normal', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(161, 105, NULL, 'SAICT Official Dismissed Following Controversial Edsa Busway Incident', 'In a move that underscores the importance of accountability in public service, a senior official from the Department of Information and Communications Technology\'s (DICT) Support for the Advancement of Information and Communications Technology (SAICT) program has been dismissed following an incident that occurred on the Edsa Busway. The decision, announced recently, has sparked a wave of discussions regarding the governance and operational protocols of public transportation systems.\r\n\r\nThe Edsa Busway, a vital transportation route in Metro Manila, has become a focal point for commuters seeking efficient and reliable transit options. However, the incident involving the SAICT official has raised serious concerns about the management and oversight of this critical infrastructure. Reports indicate that the official was involved in actions that compromised the safety and efficiency of the busway operations, leading to significant disruptions for thousands of daily commuters.\r\n\r\nEyewitness accounts detail a chaotic scene where the official\'s interference not only delayed bus operations but also created a potential safety hazard for both passengers and drivers. Such actions are particularly alarming in a city where traffic congestion is already a pressing issue. Commuters expressed frustration over the incident, highlighting the need for stricter adherence to protocols by officials tasked with overseeing public transport.\r\n\r\nThe dismissal of the SAICT official serves as a reminder of the ramifications of mismanagement in public service roles. As the government aims to modernize transportation systems and improve the quality of life for its citizens, incidents like these illustrate the necessity for accountability at every level. It is essential that officials uphold the standards expected of them, particularly in transportation sectors where the stakes are high.\r\n\r\nIn response to the incident, the DICT has reiterated its commitment to ensuring that all personnel adhere to established guidelines and protocols. The department is currently reviewing its training procedures to better equip officials with the necessary skills and knowledge to manage public transportation systems effectively. This includes enhancing awareness of the impact their actions can have on the daily lives of commuters.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, the incident has prompted calls from various sectors for a more transparent and accountable governance framework within the transportation system. Advocacy groups have emphasized the importance of citizen engagement in monitoring public officials, urging the public to voice concerns and report any misconduct. Such community involvement can help create a culture of accountability and responsibility among government personnel.\r\n\r\nAs the Edsa Busway continues to serve as a lifeline for many commuters in Metro Manila, the focus must remain on ensuring its smooth operation. The recent dismissal of the SAICT official should act as a catalyst for broader discussions about the management of public transport in the Philippines. The hope is that this incident will lead to improvements in oversight, training, and ultimately, the commuter experience.\r\n\r\nIn conclusion, the Edsa Busway incident has not only led to the dismissal of a public official but has also highlighted the critical importance of accountability in public service. As Metro Manila continues to grapple with transportation challenges, it is crucial for officials to prioritize the safety, efficiency, and reliability of the systems they oversee. The path forward must involve collective efforts from both the government and the community to ensure a better, more efficient public transportation future for all.', 47, 1, 10, 'uploads/thumb_699670af7afb28.26841740.jpg', NULL, NULL, 'manual', 1, 0, NULL, 1, '2026-02-19 03:43:18', '2026-02-19 03:43:18', '2026-02-19 11:43:18', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'normal', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(162, 104, NULL, 'Finding the Right AI: Choosing the Safest Option for You', 'In the rapidly evolving landscape of artificial intelligence, concerns about safety, ethics, and privacy have become paramount. With a plethora of AI tools available, users often find themselves asking: what’s the ‘safest’ AI to use? While there isn’t a one-size-fits-all answer, understanding the characteristics of safer AI options can guide individuals and businesses in making informed choices.\r\n\r\nSafety in AI encompasses various dimensions, including data privacy, algorithmic bias, transparency, and user control. Users should consider these factors when evaluating AI tools for their specific needs. Here, we explore some of the key features that contribute to an AI\'s safety credentials.\r\n\r\nOne of the primary indicators of a safe AI system is transparency. Users should look for AI tools that openly communicate how they operate, what data they use, and the decision-making processes involved. Companies like OpenAI and Google research emphasize transparency, sharing their methodologies and findings with the public. A transparent AI system allows users to understand potential biases and limitations, fostering trust and accountability.\r\n\r\nIn an age where data breaches are commonplace, prioritizing AI systems that prioritize user privacy is essential. Safe AI platforms implement strict data protection measures, such as encryption and anonymization. Tools that allow users to retain control over their data, giving them the option to opt in or out, are generally safer choices. For instance, many reputable AI services provide clear privacy policies outlining how user data is collected, used, and stored.\r\n\r\nAlgorithmic bias is a significant concern in AI, as biased data can lead to unfair and discriminatory outcomes. Safer AI systems actively work to identify and mitigate biases in their algorithms. Companies that conduct regular audits and updates to their AI models demonstrate a commitment to fairness. Look for platforms that offer explanations for their AI-driven decisions, as this can help users understand and challenge potential biases.\r\n\r\nThe safest AI tools empower users with control over how the technology operates. This includes providing options for customization, allowing users to tailor the AI to their specific needs and preferences. AI systems that allow users to adjust settings, such as the level of interaction or the scope of data used, promote a safer and more personalized experience.\r\n\r\nBefore adopting an AI tool, consulting expert reviews and user feedback can provide valuable insights into its safety. Engaging with communities that focus on AI ethics, such as AI ethics forums or tech-related subreddits, can help users discover which tools are deemed safe by experts and peers alike. Platforms that foster positive user experiences and have a track record of addressing concerns are often more reliable.\r\n\r\nAs artificial intelligence becomes increasingly integrated into our daily lives, selecting the safest AI tools is crucial for protecting both personal and organizational interests. By prioritizing transparency, data privacy, bias mitigation, user control, and community feedback, users can navigate the AI landscape with confidence. Remember that while no AI can be entirely free of risks, informed choices can significantly enhance safety and reliability in your AI interactions. Stay engaged, stay informed, and choose wisely as you explore the myriad of AI options available today.', 54, 1, 10, 'uploads/thumb_69966e75140332.34237233.jpg', NULL, NULL, 'manual', 1, 0, NULL, 1, '2026-02-19 03:43:25', '2026-02-19 03:43:25', '2026-02-19 11:43:25', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'normal', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(163, 103, NULL, 'Metrobank Soars: Record P49.7-B Profit Marks a Landmark Year', 'MANILA, Philippines – Metropolitan Bank & Trust Co. (Metrobank) has achieved a historic financial milestone, announcing a net profit of P49.7 billion for the fiscal year ending 2025. This record profit not only reflects the bank\'s operational excellence but also underscores its resilience amidst a dynamic economic landscape, confirming its stature as a leading player in the Philippine banking sector.\r\n\r\nThe impressive profit figure marks a significant leap from previous earnings, showcasing a robust growth trajectory that has been fueled by a strategic focus on enhancing net interest income and diversifying revenue streams. The bank\'s management credited this achievement to a mix of effective asset quality management, disciplined lending practices, and an expanded range of non-interest income sources.\r\n\r\nIn an official statement, Metrobank highlighted that net interest income continued to be a primary driver of profitability, benefiting from an increase in loan demand and a favorable interest rate environment. The bank reported strong performance across various lending segments, including corporate and consumer loans, which contributed significantly to the overall growth.\r\n\r\nMoreover, Metrobank\'s efforts to diversify its income sources have paid off, with non-interest revenues—comprising fees from transactions, investment banking activities, and wealth management services—seeing substantial growth. This diversification strategy has not only bolstered the bank’s earnings but also provided a buffer against market volatility.\r\n\r\n\"The outstanding results are a testament to our commitment to maintaining a strong balance sheet, ensuring asset quality, and providing exceptional service to our clients,\" said Metrobank President Fabian S. Dee during a press briefing. \"We remain focused on our strategic initiatives that prioritize sustainable growth and innovation in our service offerings.\"\r\n\r\nThe bank\'s prudent approach to risk management has also been a crucial factor in achieving this record profit. By maintaining a high level of asset quality, Metrobank has effectively minimized non-performing loans, further enhancing its financial stability. This proactive stance has allowed the bank to navigate potential challenges in the economic environment, including fluctuations in interest rates and external market pressures.\r\n\r\nInvestors and stakeholders have reacted positively to the announcement, with Metrobank’s stock price reflecting increased confidence in the bank’s future performance. Analysts believe the bank\'s solid financial results will likely attract more investments, further cementing its position in the competitive banking landscape.\r\n\r\nLooking ahead, Metrobank aims to continue its growth momentum by leveraging digital transformation initiatives and expanding its reach within underserved segments of the market. The bank has committed to investing in technology and infrastructure to enhance customer experience and streamline operations.\r\n\r\nIn conclusion, Metrobank\'s record P49.7 billion profit in 2025 highlights its financial resilience and strategic acumen. As the bank continues to adapt to changing market conditions, its strong performance serves as a beacon of stability and growth in the Philippine banking industry. With a firm foundation and an eye towards innovation, Metrobank is poised for continued success in the years to come.', 49, 1, 10, 'uploads/thumb_69966cf2b2e843.12174412.webp', NULL, NULL, 'manual', 1, 0, NULL, 1, '2026-02-19 03:43:28', '2026-02-19 03:43:28', '2026-02-19 11:43:28', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'normal', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(164, 102, NULL, 'AsteroidOS 2.0: A New Era for Open Smartwatches', 'AsteroidOS has officially unveiled its 2.0 release, marking a significant milestone for those invested in open-source smartwatch technology. This new version seeks to provide a robust and appealing platform for users while simultaneously offering developers a valuable opportunity to innovate and engage with the community. Built on a Linux foundation, AsteroidOS stands as a free alternative to proprietary operating systems like Google’s Wear OS and Apple’s watchOS, promoting user autonomy and privacy through its community-driven approach.\r\n\r\nThe latest update introduces a suite of enhancements designed to elevate the user experience. Notable features include an always-on display, tilt-to-wake functionality, and palm-to-sleep capabilities. Additionally, users will find new apps, such as a heart rate monitor, a compass, and a step counter, alongside a fun game called Diamonds. The complete redesign of the QuickSettings menu, now dubbed the QuickPanel, allows for greater customization and improved usability. Other significant improvements include a Nightstand mode for bedside use, enhanced app designs, and system performance upgrades that ensure smoother animations and longer battery life. AsteroidOS 2.0 also broadens its compatibility, supporting 15 new smartwatch models, thus expanding accessibility for users worldwide.', 54, 1, 5, 'uploads/thumb_69966b63e502c1.36810032.jpg', NULL, NULL, 'manual', 1, 0, NULL, 1, '2026-02-19 03:43:32', '2026-02-19 03:43:32', '2026-02-19 11:43:32', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'normal', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(165, 101, NULL, 'TNT Welcomes Towering Talent: Bol Bol\'s PBA Debut', 'Towering basketball sensation Bol Bol has arrived in the Philippines to join TNT Tropang 5G for their championship pursuit in the PBA 50th Season Commissioner\'s Cup. The 7-foot-3 NBA veteran, who previously played for the Denver Nuggets, Orlando Magic, and Phoenix Suns, was greeted at Ninoy Aquino International Airport by team manager Jojo Lastimosa. As the son of legendary NBA player Manute Bol, who was known for being 7-foot-6, the 26-year-old American-South Sudanese athlete is expected to be one of the most high-profile imports in PBA history, bringing significant anticipation and excitement to the league.', 56, 1, 5, 'uploads/thumb_69966236962b12.61652336.jpg', NULL, NULL, 'manual', 1, 0, NULL, 1, '2026-02-19 03:43:36', '2026-02-19 03:43:36', '2026-02-19 11:43:36', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'normal', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(166, 98, NULL, 'New Fossil Shows Dinosaurs Were More Unique Than We Thought', 'For over 200 years, scientists have studied plant-eating dinosaurs known as Iguanodontians, a group famous for their beaked mouths and strong back legs. Now, a team led by France’s CNRS has uncovered something completely unexpected in China: a new species called Haolong dongi. What makes this fossil so extraordinary isn’t just the nearly complete skeleton—it’s the skin. Thanks to rare preservation and advanced imaging tools, researchers were able to examine skin cells that are about 125 million years old, an almost unheard-of level of detail in dinosaur fossils.  Even more surprising, this dinosaur’s body was covered in hollow spikes made from skin, not bone—something never before seen in any dinosaur. Scientists believe these unusual spines may have helped protect it from predators, much like a porcupine’s quills, but they might also have played a role in controlling body temperature or sensing the environment. The discovery, published in Nature Ecology & Evolution, suggests dinosaurs were even more diverse and inventive in their body designs than we once imagined.\n\n---\nAuthor: Shelwin Buenaventura\nSource: MBC Chat\nPublished: February 18, 2026\n', 95, 1, 8, 'uploads/chat_media/2026/02/thumb_69956a5bf01d4.jpg', NULL, NULL, 'manual', 1, 0, NULL, 1, '2026-02-19 03:43:41', '2026-02-19 03:43:41', '2026-02-19 11:43:41', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'normal', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(167, 121, NULL, 'P70 million illegal cigarettes seized in Pampanga', 'MANILA, Philippines — Suspected illegaly manufactured cigarettes worth P70 million were seized on Monday following a raid in Pampanga on another warehouse, the fourth to be discovered by authorities this month.\r\n\r\nThe discovery of the warehouse in Barangay San Pablo Libutad in San Simon town was based on information provided by a concerned citizen, who notified police after having watched a press conference held by Interior and Local Government Secretary Jonvic Remulla about the raid on three illegal tobacco facilities.\r\n\r\nA few hours after the news conference, Philippine National Police chief Gen. Jose Melencio Nartatez Jr. said the PNP received a call from the informant, who told them about the existence of a similar facility in Golden Sun 999 Business Park.\r\n\r\nNartatez dispatched members of the police Criminal Detection and Investigation Group, who confirmed the presence of illicit cigarettes in the warehouse.\r\n\r\nThe raiding team seized 1,192 master cases of assorted cigarette brands.\r\n\r\nNo one was arrested in the raid.\r\n\r\nThe PNP has yet to confirm if the factory is related to three warehouses that were earlier discovered in San Simon, Mexico and San Fernando.\r\n\r\nThe raid on the warehouses on Feb. 11, 13 and 14 resulted in the seizure of P275 million worth of tobacco products and equipment used for manufacturing cigarettes.\r\n\r\nRemulla said two incumbent congressmen from Central Luzon are being investigated for being the alleged masterminds behind illegal cigarette factories in the country.\r\n\r\nHe declined to name the congressmen, citing case buildup still being conducted by police.\r\n\r\nThe congressmen have been placed under surveillance after a person linked to them attempted to bribe members of the Highway Patrol Group who seized tobacco products worth millions of pesos.\r\n\r\n“So far, that’s the only link we have on them, and we are not sure if this is sufficient to have them convicted in court,” Remulla said.\r\n\r\nThe congressmen reportedly tried to meet with Remulla through an emissary, but he rejected their request.\r\n\r\nP188 million seized cigarettes destroyed\r\nThe Bureau of Customs (BOC) on Monday destroyed 4,360 master cases of illicit cigarettes valued at P188 million, which were seized in separate operations in Northern Mindanao.\r\n\r\nThe contraband was destroyed at the compound of the Mindanao Container Terminal in Tagoloan, Misamis Oriental.\r\n\r\nThe ceremony was witnessed by BOC Deputy Commissioner Romeo Allan Rosales along with members of different law enforcement units as well as the military.\r\n\r\nRep. Yevgeny Vincente Emano of the second district of Misamis Oriental described the volume of confiscated contraband as unprecedented and among the largest in the country.\r\n\r\nRosales warned people and groups involved in the illicit cigarette trade noting the bureau would continue pursuing violators.\r\n\r\nThe destruction of the contraband was part of the celebration of the BOC’s 50th anniversary.', 50, 1, 12, 'uploads/thumb_69980abe5a5b02.89363137.jpg', NULL, NULL, 'manual', 1, 0, NULL, 1, '2026-02-20 07:19:08', '2026-02-20 07:19:08', '2026-02-20 15:19:08', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'normal', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(168, 120, 160, 'Gauff tips hat off to crowd-drawer Eala', 'MANILA, Philippines — World No. 4 tennister Coco Gauff lauded Alex Eala for “bringing a new demographic” to tennis, as the two faced off against each other before a rowdy crowd in the Dubai Duty Free Tennis Championships.\r\n\r\nGauff defeated Eala in dominating fashion, 6-0, 6-2, in their quarterfinal matchup late Thursday evening (Manila time).\r\n\r\nBut despite the score showing Eala being overpowered, the crowd did not make it seem that way.\r\n\r\nChants of “Let’s go Alex!” and “A-lex! A-lex!” showered center court, as they tried to rally the Filipina to a comeback victory that did not come.\r\n\r\nAfter the match, Gauff voiced appreciation to how the crowd cheered.\r\n\r\n“Yeah, thank you guys for coming out here, and I know you\'re mostly supporting Alex, but I have to say it is great to be on a crowded court,” she said during the post-match interview. \r\n\r\n“I played this tournament for many years and to see the stadium full that means a lot.” \r\n\r\nGauff, easily one of the most popular tennis players in the world, said that she also relished the cheers for her opponent.\r\n\r\n“I’d like to thank Alex for bringing a new demographic to the sport. I really appreciate it. I think it\'s great. I know sometimes it\'s tough when you\'re playing against a home crowd, but I think that it\'s great for the sport,” the 21-year-old American stressed. \r\n\r\n“So keep being enthusiastic and keep rooting for your player.”\r\n\r\nGauff added that when the crowd cheered for Eala, she just imagined that they are cheering her name.\r\n\r\n“Honestly, I had a similar match at French Open last year, so I brought that mindset today of just trying to whenever you guys were cheering for Alex I was pretending that it was my name and I think it helped me a lot,” she said. \r\n\r\n“If you can\'t beat them, you got to join them.” \r\n\r\nEala is one of the fastest rising stars in tennis today. \r\n\r\nAfter her miracle run in the Miami Open last year, she has competed against the best of the best, taking down numerous top 20 players.\r\n\r\nIn Dubai, she added former tournament champion Jasmine Paolini to her list after she defeated the Italian, 6-1, 7-6(5), in the Round of 32.\r\n\r\nAnd in every tournament she plays in, the Filipina brings crowds so rowdy that the umpire usually reminds the fans not to cheer during play. \r\n\r\nGauff will take on Elina Svitolina in the semifinal of the Dubai tourney.', NULL, 1, 12, 'uploads/thumb_69980a324e68b.jpg', NULL, NULL, 'manual', 1, 1, 'developing', 3, '2026-02-20 07:19:12', '2026-02-20 07:19:12', '2026-02-20 15:19:12', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'normal', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(169, 119, 160, 'Eala bows to Gauff, crashes out of Dubai Tennis Championships', 'MANILA, Philippines — The spirited run of Alex Eala in the Dubai Duty Free Tennis Championships has ended. \r\n\r\nEala slammed into a brick wall that is World No. 4 Coco Gauff, 6-0, 6-2, in their quarterfinal round clash Thursday evening (Manila time). \r\n\r\nEala was at the receiving end of a dominant win by the American, who grabbed the victory in an hour and seven minutes.\r\n\r\n\"I was a bit better today. I could have served a little bit better, but I made it in when it mattered,\" Gauff said in the post-match interview.\r\n\r\n\"Alex is a tough competitor and even when I was up, I knew that she could come back at any given moment. I\'ve seen her do it before.\" \r\n\r\nThe Filipina was simply outmatched right from the get-go, yielding 15 unforced errors in the first set as she was bageled. \r\n\r\nGauff’s dominance continued on in the second set as she simply schooled the 20-year-old, much to Eala’s frustration. \r\n\r\nThe World No. 47 tennister finally put herself on the board in the fifth and sixth games of the second set to inch closer, 2-4, and she seemed to have found a second wind as the crowd continued trying to pump up the pride of the Philippines. \r\n\r\nBut Gauff found her groove anew, finishing off the match with wins in the seventh and eighth games. \r\n\r\nThe American punched in 29 service points to Eala\'s 14, while also winning 26 receiving points to her opponent\'s 19. \r\n\r\nAnd while Gauff had eight double faults, the Filipina had 33 unforced errors to her opponent\'s 19. \r\n\r\nBefore falling against the Florida native, Eala defeated Hailey Baptiste, 2024 tournament champion Jasmine Paolini, and battle-tested veteran Sorana Cirstea. \r\n\r\nGauff, for her part, will now face either World No. 67 Antonia Ruzic or World No. 9 Elina Svitolina in the semifinals. \r\n\r\nIn the other pairing, World No. 5 Jessica Pegula will take on World No. 6 Amanda Anisimova for a final berth. \r\n\r\nThe former defeated Clara Tauson in three sets, 6-3, 2-6, 6-4, while the latter dethroned defending champion Mirra Andreeva, 2-6, 7-5, 7-6(4).', NULL, 1, 12, 'uploads/thumb_699809da8b34f.jpg', NULL, NULL, 'manual', 1, 1, 'developing', 2, '2026-02-20 07:19:15', '2026-02-20 07:19:15', '2026-02-20 15:19:15', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'normal', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(170, 118, 160, 'Eala still a big winner with ranking points, cash earned despite Dubai exit', 'MANILA, Philippines — Filipina tennis ace Alex Eala has bowed out of the Dubai Duty Free Tennis Championships. \r\n\r\nBut surely, she will not be going home empty-handed. \r\n\r\nThe 20-year-old, World No. 47 tennister will be bringing home millions of pesos after her quarterfinal run in the WTA 1000 tournament. \r\n\r\nAccording to the Women’s Tennis Association (WTA) website, the tournament has a $4,088,211 prize money at stake. \r\n\r\nFor quarterfinalists, the prize money is at $98,500, or approximately P5.7 million. \r\n\r\nThose who were also booted out from the Last Eight — Antonia Ruzic, Clara Tauson and Mirra Andreeva — also brought home the same prize money. \r\n\r\nThis is double compared to the $49,250 to be takeb home by those who competed in the Round of 16.\r\n\r\nThe WTA said that semifinalists of the tournament will earn $197,000 (P11.4 million); the runner-up, $385,000 (P22.4 million); and the champion, $665,000 (P38.6 million). \r\n\r\nBut money is just one side of the coin for those competing in the tourney. \r\n\r\nEala also netted 215 ranking points after her quarterfinal exit.\r\n\r\nWith this, the Filipina is expected to reach a new career-high of World No. 32, according to the live WTA rankings.\r\n\r\nThis is the highest ranking for the 20-year-old, whose last career-high was No. 40.\r\n\r\nThe semifinalists will be awarded 390 points; the runner-up, 650 points; and the champion, a whopping 1,000 points.\r\n\r\nAfter her Middle East Swing, Eala will see action in the Indian Wells Open, which set to start March 4.\r\n\r\nShe is also listed in this year’s Miami Open, where she put the world on notice with huge wins last year.', NULL, 1, 12, 'uploads/thumb_699809192f5d0.jpg', NULL, NULL, 'manual', 1, 1, 'developing', 1, '2026-02-20 07:19:23', '2026-02-20 07:19:23', '2026-02-20 15:19:23', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'normal', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(171, 117, 156, 'In Cebu, ‘impeach her’ call takes spotlight amid anti-dynasty talks', 'MANILA, Philippines — Despite the program at the University of the Philippines (UP) Cebu City campus focusing on anti-political dynasty discussions, a resident’s call to impeach Vice President Sara Duterte stole the spotlight amid concerns that her 2028 presidential bid could weaken accountability.\r\n\r\nDuring the House of Representatives’ committee on suffrage and electoral reforms’ public consultation on Wednesday, private citizen R.A. Fortuna said:\r\n\r\n“First of all, allow me to request the members of Congress here: two words—Impeach her,” Fortuna said, drawing cheers from the crowd at UP Cebu.\r\n\r\n“I didn’t say ‘him,’ I said ‘her,’” he added.\r\n\r\nFortuna did not clarify who he was referring to, but currently, only one impeachable official has pending complaints before the House: Vice President Sara Duterte.\r\n\r\nAs of writing, four complaints against Duterte are lodged with House Speaker Faustino “Bojie” Dy III, citing alleged misuse of confidential funds in her offices, threats against ranking officials, and other possible violations of the 1987 Constitution.\r\n\r\nThe first two complaints from the Makabayan Coalition and civil society groups were filed on February 2. The third, from clergy members and lawyers, was submitted on February 9, while the fourth, from lawyer Nathaniel Cabrera, was forwarded to the House on February 18.', 98, 1, 13, 'uploads/thumb_69980917ae32f2.78603284.jpeg', NULL, NULL, 'manual', 1, 1, 'developing', 2, '2026-02-20 07:19:26', '2026-02-20 07:19:26', '2026-02-20 15:19:26', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'normal', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(172, 116, 156, '4th impeachment rap vs Sara Duterte transmitted to Speaker Dy’s office', 'MANILA, Philippines — The fourth impeachment complaint against Vice President Sara Duterte has been transmitted to the Office of House of Representatives Speaker Faustino “Bojie” Dy III, the Office of the Secretary General said on Thursday.\r\n\r\nIn a statement, the office of House Secretary General Cheloy Garafil confirmed that the complaint filed by lawyer Nathaniel Cabrera, endorsed by Deputy Speaker Paolo Ortega and Manila Rep. Bienvenido Abante Jr., has already been received by Dy’s office.\r\n\r\nThis means four complaints are already pending before Dy, awaiting inclusion in the Order of Business.\r\n\r\n“A fourth impeachment complaint filed against Vice President Sara Duterte was formally received by the Office of the Secretary General at 6:34 p.m. on Wednesday and has been transmitted to the Office of Speaker Faustino ‘Bojie’ G. Dy III today, Thursday, in accordance with established House rules,” Garafil’s office said.\r\n\r\n“The verified complaint was filed by Atty. Nathaniel G. Cabrera and endorsed by House Committee on Human Rights Chair Bienvenido “Benny” Abante Jr. and Deputy Speaker Paolo Ortega V.  The OSG’s role is purely ministerial, confined to receiving and transmitting pleadings and documents filed with the House,” it added.', 48, 1, 13, 'uploads/thumb_699807f1d3d08.jpg', NULL, NULL, 'manual', 1, 1, 'developing', 1, '2026-02-20 07:19:29', '2026-02-20 07:19:29', '2026-02-20 15:19:29', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'normal', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(173, 113, NULL, 'Series of diesel price hikes cued to enter third month', 'MANILA, Philippines — Filipino motorists are bracing for yet another round of fuel price increases next week, marking a concerning trend that sees diesel prices on track for their ninth consecutive weekly hike. This sustained uptrend is poised to push the overall series of petroleum product price adjustments into its third month, placing further strain on household budgets and business operations across the archipelago.\r\n\r\nAccording to initial market indications shared by Leo Bellas, president of Jetti Petroleum, on Friday, the per-liter price of diesel is anticipated to climb by an estimated 40 centavos to 60 centavos. This projected increase, while seemingly modest per liter, accumulates significantly over weeks and months, especially for high-volume consumers like public transport operators and logistics companies.\r\n\r\nThe primary catalyst for this persistent upward pressure on fuel prices stems from escalating geopolitical tensions in the Middle East. Bellas specifically cited \"concerns over military activities in the region\" which have significantly \"increased the likelihood of US strikes on Iran.\" This heightened state of alert and potential for direct conflict has dampened any hope for a swift diplomatic resolution, creating an environment of uncertainty that directly impacts global oil markets. Investors and traders react to such developments by factoring in a \"risk premium,\" driving up crude oil prices on fears of supply disruptions, particularly from the critical Strait of Hormuz, a vital chokepoint for a substantial portion of the world\'s oil shipments.\r\n\r\nBeyond the immediate threat of conflict, Bellas also highlighted another crucial factor offsetting any potential price relief: \"rising freight and premium due to geopolitical risks.\" The instability in key shipping lanes, especially in regions like the Red Sea and Gulf of Aden, has led to increased insurance costs for vessels, longer rerouting journeys to avoid conflict zones, and a general scarcity of ships willing to traverse high-risk areas. These operational challenges translate directly into higher shipping costs for refined petroleum products, which are then passed on to importing countries like the Philippines. The \"premium\" refers to the additional cost added to the base price of oil or refined products due to perceived supply risks or increased demand for secure, timely delivery.\r\n\r\nInterestingly, Bellas noted that \"this week’s gasoline MOPS [Mean of Platts Singapore] prices have actually softened due to healthy regional inventories and supply.\" MOPS is the pricing benchmark for refined petroleum products in Asia, and a softening here would typically suggest a potential for a price rollback. However, the pervasive influence of rising freight costs and the geopolitical risk premium have effectively \"offset the prospect of a potential price rollback\" for gasoline, meaning consumers will likely see either minimal changes or even slight increases for gasoline as well, despite favorable underlying supply conditions.\r\n\r\nThe cumulative effect of these price hikes is expected to ripple through the Philippine economy. Consumers will face higher costs for transportation, and businesses will grapple with increased operational expenses, potentially leading to inflationary pressures on basic goods and services. Public utility vehicle (PUV) operators, particularly jeepney and bus drivers, are often among the first to feel the pinch, prompting calls for fare adjustments or government subsidies to maintain their livelihoods. The government, in turn, will be closely monitoring global oil developments and domestic inflation, with potential considerations for measures such as fuel subsidies or adjustments to excise taxes to mitigate the impact on the populace. The outlook remains challenging, with Filipino consumers heavily reliant on global geopolitical stability for any respite from the ongoing fuel price surge.', 49, 1, 13, 'uploads/thumb_6998067f79ef18.23679274.jpeg', NULL, NULL, 'manual', 1, 0, NULL, 1, '2026-02-20 07:19:32', '2026-02-20 07:19:32', '2026-02-20 15:19:32', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'normal', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(174, 112, NULL, 'PNP backs Marcos order to craft strategy vs ’dirty money’', 'MANILA, Philippines — Philippine National Police (PNP) Chief Gen. Jose Melencio Nartatez Jr. said the agency supports President Ferdinand Marcos Jr.’s order for the government to craft a national strategy against money laundering.\r\n\r\n“The PNP is fully committed to President Marcos’ directive. We are ready to integrate our investigative powers with [the] AMLC (Anti-Money Laundering Council) in running after organized crime groups and syndicates,” Nartatez said in a statement on Friday.\r\n\r\n“High-risk sectors such as real estate, casinos, and import/export businesses will be closely monitored while international cooperation with foreign law enforcement agencies will be strengthened to track illicit funds entering or leaving the Philippines,” he added.\r\n\r\nThe directive came through Memorandum Circular No. 113 dated Feb. 12.\r\n\r\nThe memorandum ordered government agencies concerned to “actively participate” in drafting and to ensure their institutional plans were aligned with the National Anti-Money Laundering, Counter-Terrorism and Counter-Proliferation Financing Strategy for 2026–2030.\r\n\r\nIt also tasked the AMLC in particular to provide “technical and administrative support, issue timelines and monitor compliance” of the government agencies concerned.\r\n\r\nNartatez said the PNP will “enhance inter-agency cooperation, share data and participate in joint operations” to support the president’s directive.\r\n\r\nThe top cop noted that the police force, particularly its Anti-Cybercrime Group and Criminal Investigation and Detection Group, was undergoing training in financial forensics and detecting trends in financial crimes and money laundering.\r\n\r\n“The PNP is also upgrading its digital infrastructure, technologies, and data analytics tools for detecting suspicious financial transactions, including cross-border alerts,” he added.', 46, 1, 13, 'uploads/thumb_699805ab3e7390.21456873.jpeg', NULL, NULL, 'manual', 1, 0, NULL, 1, '2026-02-20 07:19:35', '2026-02-20 07:19:35', '2026-02-20 15:19:35', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'normal', 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
